WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:13.000
Good morning.

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:25.000
This is Emilye Crosby with Mr. Reggie Robinson on December 11, 2015 at the Library of Congress with the Civil Rights History Project,

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:33.000
and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture and John Bishop with also with us.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:35.000
Good morning, Mr. Robinson.

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:36.000
Good morning, y'all.

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:41.000
It's nice to have you here, and to glad you're here to participate in the project.

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:45.000
Well, it's been an uphill struggle, as you know.

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:48.000
But they come a time.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:50.000
They come a time.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:56.000
Can you tell us when and where you were born and about your family?

00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:12.000
Well, I was born in Baltimore, Maryland, October 2, 1939, to Leroy and Leo Vesta, L-E-O-V-E-S-T-E-R Robinson.

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:16.000
My mother's maiden name was Jenkins.

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:19.000
I had one brother.

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:24.000
I have one brother still living, who was the oldest.

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:28.000
His name was Leroy.

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:36.000
I had a sister named Lula Jean, and she was between the two of us.

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:39.000
It was only three siblings.

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:41.000
You were the baby?

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:43.000
I was the youngest.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:45.000
What did your parents do for living?

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:56.000
Well, my dad worked at Bethlehem Steel for 39 years until he retired.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:01.000
And he died a month after he retired.

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:04.000
Yes, yes.

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:10.000
But my mother did often on kind of housework and stuff.

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:16.000
She didn't really go to work until I was in the first grade.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:21.000
Then they started hiring babysitters, and then I'd go to neighbor's houses.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:28.000
And while she went out and did piecework or whatever to bring in a little bit more.

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:42.000
I went to Dunbar High School until about the tenth and a half grades.

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:53.000
When I discovered that I didn't quite understand what French was going to do for me.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:58.000
But I was looking out the window, and I knew what I could do on the streets.

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:02.000
So the streets won.

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:14.000
And I was doing pretty well out there until the little job that I had kind of fell apart for all kinds of reasons.

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:19.000
And then I was frustrated because I didn't know what to do.

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:24.000
And it was all kinds of things to get into.

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:37.000
I have a cousin by the name of Josephine Thorn, who at that time was a supervisor at Social Security.

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:48.000
And she had went to a small business college called Cortez Peters Business College.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:55.000
She convinced my father, well she convinced me first that I needed to stop doing what I was doing.

00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:57.000
And do something.

00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:02.000
So she convinced my father to give me another chance.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:07.000
And I enrolled into Cortez Peters Business College.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:17.000
Now Cortez Peters Business College was founded by a black man by the name of Cortez Peters.

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:31.000
It was either royal typewriter or underwear typewriter that financed him because he could type somewhere like 150 words a minute.

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:38.000
He advertised by having him type with an entire orchestra.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:41.000
But they gave him money.

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:51.000
And he established three schools, one in Washington, DC, one in Baltimore, and one in Chicago.

00:04:51.000 --> 00:05:05.000
And basically was teaching blacks how to pass government tests, teaching girls how to do shorthand.

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:16.000
They taught guys business law accounting, and everybody had to take typing and learn how to make and type one of them stencils.

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:23.000
You learn what blackout was and all of those little fancy office things.

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:35.000
Then in 60 when the students at Greensboro sat in and things broke loose.

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:41.000
There was a group that was formed in Baltimore called the Civic Interest Group.

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:44.000
It was the student group.

00:05:44.000 --> 00:06:02.000
And at the same time the dean of my school, Walter Dixon, was also the City Councilman in Baltimore who had just introduced a public accommodations bill.

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:15.000
He kind of ordered me, I was kind of like under his thumb because he kept keep telling me my daddy didn't send me that waste money.

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:25.000
So he kept me under his thumb until he sent me to represent our school at the big school meetings.

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:32.000
When I got there I met a lot of people from all of the colleges in Maryland it looked like.

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:38.000
But Morgan was kind of like the head, Hancho and things.

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:44.000
So I got involved with the city ends around Baltimore until I got involved.

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:54.000
I worked my way into the group until we started moving from direct action to voter registration

00:06:54.000 --> 00:07:00.000
where we got some money to do voter registration.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:10.000
And at that time it was concentrated in one general area which was Clarence Mitchell Junior's area.

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:18.000
And we raised, oh I think it was about 30,000 people in a very short period of time.

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:25.000
So money was coming in and money had to be accounted for and we had an advisory group and everything.

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:31.000
So I got to be because I knew a little bit about accounting and I had worked my way into the group.

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:38.000
I became the treasurer of the civic interest group.

00:07:38.000 --> 00:08:02.000
We did that and then at the June meeting in which Clarence Mitchell went to and came back and reported that the overall SNCC group was getting ready to move towards voter registration and direct action.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:23.000
And also at that time Clarence's grandmother had said that the NAACP, she was president of the NAACP and she had said that she was not going to get us out of jail anymore, bail and everything.

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:31.000
And then Clarence had to make a decision as to whether to continue with us or go with his family.

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:40.000
So Clarence went with his family so that seat at SNCC from Maryland became open.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:09:00.000
I opted to take the seat to get to go. I wanted to see the night before I left we were at a party and I got hit in the eye with a pretzel.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:10.000
So before I went I had to get some ice kind of stuff done so I had this black patch over my eye.

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:17.000
So my orders were from Civic Interest Group because by this time everything was happening in the South.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:28.000
We were getting a student voice and we were in contact with all of these guys that Chuck McDew and everything going on in Nashville and everything that's happening everywhere.

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:46.000
We in touch with it. So my orders were to bring the next meeting back to Baltimore and at that time, King had also stepped in because he's gotten the word that we're thinking about moving on Mississippi.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:55.000
So he, him and his boys is out saying, you know, y'all can't do that, you're going to get killed and everything else though.

00:09:55.000 --> 00:10:10.000
So I go to the SNCC meeting in Louisville, Kentucky and July of, you know, I went in June of 61.

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:16.000
June of 61.

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:25.000
When I went into the meeting, of course everybody I introduced myself and of course everybody thought I got injured in battle.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:31.000
I didn't tell anybody.

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:38.000
So of course they moved around me very easily and we were there for the weekend.

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:52.000
This is, I guess, Friday night we're coming in and introducing ourselves and then by Saturday night we're having, we've been going through all through Saturday of fussing and cussing and everything.

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:58.000
And so we're now an am breeding house on Saturday night.

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:11.000
But I'm still not in with the guys because they don't know who I am and I don't know if I should say this but Clarence didn't really have a reputation of being inside the group and working.

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:14.000
He was known to be doing other things.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:17.000
So I was trying to find out what was going on.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:34.000
Anyway, I was standing on Anne Braden's porch drinking a beer by myself and this little lady walks up to me and she says, son, I know who you are.

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:43.000
And I says, I don't know nobody in this group and she says, where's your people from?

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:52.000
I told her my father was from Smithfield, Virginia and then she says, where are you from?

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:55.000
I said, little enough Carolina.

00:11:55.000 --> 00:12:00.000
She says, oh, she says, what was your mom's middle name?

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:06.000
I said, Jenkins. She said, where was your mom's first name?

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:11.000
I said, Leo Vester. She said, oh, man, I know who you are.

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:18.000
You McKinley. I said, no, I got an uncle McKinley. She says, I know.

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:27.000
You exactly like him. This was Ella Baker. She said, you just like him. He works with me in New York.

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:33.000
And I know you're on over there because of an overdose in Baltimore.

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:41.000
And then the church I went to was involved in all kinds of Baptist connections and stuff.

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:45.000
So it was a recognized church in the Baptist conference.

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:56.000
So she would have known my aunt and my aunt, I can't even think of my aunt's name, but anyway.

00:12:57.000 --> 00:13:03.000
My cousin, Overdell and her mama was very much up in the church.

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:09.000
And so that's why she do them and very active in the community.

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:17.000
So with that happening, then Miss Baker kind of smooth away.

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:22.000
And I became a different kind of light, I guess, to chuck in the voice.

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:30.000
Here what I was saying, till I won the next meeting back to Baltimore

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:37.000
to discuss this whole thing of going down. And in the meantime, Bob Moses has already gone to Mississippi.

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:41.000
It's now about August.

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:45.000
It's getting close to August.

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:48.000
We have the meeting.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:58.000
And one of the first things we do is we will have this big rally in Baltimore at the Masonic Temple.

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:04.000
And we were going to split the proceeds with King. King was the noted speaker coming.

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:10.000
Everybody knew he was coming to town to be with us and convince us not to do whatever.

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:13.000
And we will have this big rally and everything.

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:26.000
So before the rally started, I convinced everybody, Albrook, that what we would do is we would open the meeting before the preacher got there.

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:34.000
And have our people deployed. And we would make the collection as soon as the people sat down.

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:41.000
So then we did that and then we split the money between SNCC and Civic Interest Group.

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:48.000
And so by the time Wyatt Tee Walker and the preachers got, we were going through their thing at the rally.

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:52.000
And Wyatt went to say, it's time for the collection.

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:57.000
Somebody pulled Wyatt's coat and say the collection has been done.

00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:16.000
So I had been for Dean Dixon, Miss Baker, and then I go on and do the rest.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:23.000
So you were telling me about having the collection before...

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:32.000
Okay, yes. So we did the collection and we split the money between Civic Interest Group and SNCC.

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:35.000
And of course, we're excited about what happened to Wyatt.

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:37.000
So then we went on with the meeting and everything.

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:44.000
And then it was decided that SNCC was going to do voter registration and direct action.

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:52.000
Somebody had to go in and be with Bob Moses and just Bob Moses.

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:55.000
Nobody was saying anything at the time.

00:15:55.000 --> 00:15:59.000
So I raised my hand.

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:06.000
Well, I was also recognized by the time I made my report about what voter registration we did in Baltimore.

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:10.000
They thought I was a voter registration expert.

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:17.000
But all we did in Baltimore was have a soundtrack, school buses, and went around with big music.

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:20.000
And people came out of the house.

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:24.000
Got on the buses. We took them down the gate street, had big long lines.

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:28.000
Had the big press out there, had hot dogs. Had a big party.

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:36.000
People signed up thousands of people and big scene and took people back home, party in the neighborhood.

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:43.000
Well, they thought that I knew what I was doing.

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:48.000
So I was elected to go to Mississippi.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:54.000
So when I left, what about the Mississippi?

00:16:54.000 --> 00:17:03.000
Well, like I said, I mean, I had done what I could do in Baltimore.

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:16.000
And without going into a lot of stuff, I would have probably had a lot more trouble in Baltimore than I had in Mississippi.

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:26.000
Then what I did, going to Mississippi and using my energies for that, then what I would have done if I stayed in Baltimore.

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:30.000
My life was in just as much jeopardy.

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:37.000
So I chose to be productive as I thought I was being.

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:47.000
So then, as I'm taking off for thinking I'm going to go, I take off from Baltimore to Atlanta,

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:55.000
where I'm to go change trains and go to Mississippi, go to the Delta and meet Bob Moses.

00:17:55.000 --> 00:18:04.000
When I get to Atlanta, I meet Ed King, who's our executive director at the time.

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:13.000
And Ed meets me at the train station and really in top hat and tails.

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:20.000
He had just integrated the National Symphony of Atlanta that night.

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:26.000
And he had been partying all night long with the people he had done it with.

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:36.000
And he took me to the office and sat me down and he went home and changed.

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:42.000
And then he took me around Atlanta to introduce me to the people of Atlanta.

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:53.000
And of course, at CLC at that time, we were at Auburn Avenue here and King's office was right across the street.

00:18:53.000 --> 00:19:00.000
So Ed took me in and who do we meet coming in the door?

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:06.000
But YT and Ed says in his jovial kind of way,

00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:13.000
oh, why do I like for you to meet our new field secretary?

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:18.000
And why it looked at me and said, oh, I know which one that is.

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:21.000
That's the one from Baltimore.

00:19:21.000 --> 00:19:28.000
Of course, when Ed went to someplace else and Ed and Ed and I had a private conversation,

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:33.000
I wanted me to work for SCLC of course, but anyway I said, no, no, no, I'm settled.

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:37.000
But anyway, they were really the truth and hard.

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:39.000
Oh, oh yeah, oh yeah.

00:19:39.000 --> 00:19:43.000
And especially if they had Moses and Mary.

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:48.000
Yeah, yeah, and Diane Nash and Charlie.

00:19:48.000 --> 00:19:51.000
They had everybody listed in there.

00:19:51.000 --> 00:19:57.000
But anyway, we were.

00:19:57.000 --> 00:20:00.000
Oh, after why I tried to recruit them.

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:04.000
Oh, oh, then we went back to the office and stuff.

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:11.000
And Ed got the word that I was not to go to the Delta, but to meet Bob Moses in McComb.

00:20:11.000 --> 00:20:19.000
So I took off from Atlanta, went to New Orleans, changed trains in New Orleans,

00:20:19.000 --> 00:20:23.000
took Illinois Central up to McComb.

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:32.000
At McComb, I was met by George Hitz, who was a local cab driver,

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:36.000
who George became a very good friend of mine.

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:43.000
And incidentally, all through this until today, I don't drive.

00:20:43.000 --> 00:20:49.000
So George took me from the train station to CC Bryant's.

00:20:49.000 --> 00:20:54.000
I was with Bob Moses and CC was waiting for me.

00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:57.000
And I introduced, Bob Moses introduced me around.

00:20:57.000 --> 00:21:01.000
I had to get a med Bob Moses, we talked, and I met the locals.

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:06.000
And I met, and I was introduced to Mr. Webb Orange,

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:12.000
who was better known as Super Cool Daddy.

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:17.000
And I was told that Super Cool Daddy was the man

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:21.000
to see, to do everything.

00:21:21.000 --> 00:21:25.000
So Super Cool Daddy and I walked on off.

00:21:25.000 --> 00:21:34.000
We went first to Mama Cotton's house on Wall Street, set up a housing,

00:21:34.000 --> 00:21:43.000
set up a deal to pay her, went to Mr. Plevis's to restaurant and miss Quinn,

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:48.000
set up a little thing to pay down, went down,

00:21:48.000 --> 00:21:55.000
and opened up a bank account in SNCC's name in the town.

00:21:55.000 --> 00:22:02.000
And an account at the stationery store where I rented a

00:22:02.000 --> 00:22:08.000
memograph machine and stem solos and white out and all of the stuff.

00:22:08.000 --> 00:22:13.000
We were doing business with the city because that was part of the plans

00:22:13.000 --> 00:22:15.000
that we had thought about.

00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:19.000
I mean, you do bend this, you.

00:22:19.000 --> 00:22:23.000
They kind of look at it in a different kind of way we thought.

00:22:23.000 --> 00:22:28.000
But anyway, we went on and we got set up

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:34.000
and over top of Burglund High School, over top of Burglund Supermarket

00:22:35.000 --> 00:22:38.000
was the Messade Temple.

00:22:38.000 --> 00:22:44.000
We set up a school there where we were encouraging people to come in.

00:22:44.000 --> 00:22:48.000
Well, we did canvassing.

00:22:48.000 --> 00:23:00.000
And it was my own fears, but I was canvassing in the projects with some of the local kids.

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:03.000
And there was some workmen.

00:23:03.000 --> 00:23:09.000
I could see them in this ground, in this sewer hole, in this ground hole.

00:23:09.000 --> 00:23:14.000
They were workmen, they'd minding their business, but they were white men.

00:23:14.000 --> 00:23:17.000
I was thinking that they knew what I was doing.

00:23:17.000 --> 00:23:21.000
So I was unconscious of them every moment.

00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:26.000
To almost the point that I forgot about the kids that I had with me.

00:23:27.000 --> 00:23:32.000
But that was about the one or only time that I had that kind of a fear.

00:23:32.000 --> 00:23:35.000
And they weren't paying any attention to me.

00:23:35.000 --> 00:23:40.000
So I got over that and then we went on and we set up the school.

00:23:40.000 --> 00:23:45.000
And in the school, the law of the state was,

00:23:45.000 --> 00:23:52.000
you had to interpret the Constitution of Mississippi in order to register the vote.

00:23:53.000 --> 00:23:58.000
You had to be able to read it and then interpret.

00:23:58.000 --> 00:24:03.000
And the way the registrar would do it when you come down,

00:24:03.000 --> 00:24:09.000
he would take the Constitution and flip the pages and turn to any page in the book

00:24:09.000 --> 00:24:13.000
and say, write that, read that.

00:24:13.000 --> 00:24:18.000
And if my interpretation is not what you would expose to be, then you fail.

00:24:19.000 --> 00:24:24.000
So we had the first of all teach people to read and write.

00:24:26.000 --> 00:24:32.000
We had to encourage people to come for the reasons that they were coming for.

00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:37.000
Then after we get them to read and write and be able to have the courage to pass

00:24:37.000 --> 00:24:43.000
to even take the test, it encouraged them to go down.

00:24:43.000 --> 00:24:49.000
So that's when Bob Moses would say that we'd have to always stick with these people

00:24:49.000 --> 00:24:53.000
and walk with them wherever they go.

00:24:53.000 --> 00:24:57.000
And that's when we started taking them down to the registrar's office.

00:24:57.000 --> 00:25:08.000
And Bob Moses got beaten and later on, of course, Herbert Lee, Herbert Lee got killed

00:25:08.000 --> 00:25:14.000
in the cotton gin by State Representative E.H. Hurst.

00:25:14.000 --> 00:25:19.000
And that's when the kids, when the kids start sitting in,

00:25:19.000 --> 00:25:24.000
and the kids start doing direct action in the town got involved.

00:25:24.000 --> 00:25:33.000
Because one of the things that I was told in one of my first training sessions was that

00:25:33.000 --> 00:25:38.000
we were not going into these cities to stay.

00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:47.000
You were going to either duplicate yourself or leave something there in order for people to hang on to

00:25:47.000 --> 00:25:53.000
or put them in touch with, put a group together that could connect with SNCC that could

00:25:53.000 --> 00:25:56.000
support any activity that's going on.

00:25:56.000 --> 00:26:05.000
But you want to go in and build something and leave something, not to go and make a home there.

00:26:05.000 --> 00:26:08.000
So the...

00:26:08.000 --> 00:26:11.000
So it was coming from the...

00:26:11.000 --> 00:26:12.000
... came from Ella.

00:26:12.000 --> 00:26:14.000
From the reason from the bottom up.

00:26:14.000 --> 00:26:19.000
I mean, if you go in and thinking you know it all and you're going to stay there

00:26:19.000 --> 00:26:25.000
and forever to do it, you ain't passing on enough and you ain't teaching nothing.

00:26:25.000 --> 00:26:27.000
You ain't building nothing.

00:26:27.000 --> 00:26:31.000
You just building your own kind of whatever you're looking for.

00:26:31.000 --> 00:26:35.000
You aren't giving anything to anybody.

00:26:35.000 --> 00:26:42.000
So it was always important to know that what you're doing is you're building things for somebody else to build on.

00:26:42.000 --> 00:26:47.000
So you're always working yourself out of a job.

00:26:47.000 --> 00:26:54.000
So of course the kids got involved and they started sitting in and everything.

00:26:54.000 --> 00:27:03.000
And Curtis and Hollis, Curtis Hayes and Hollis Watkins and Bobby Talbert and I think Brenda Travis,

00:27:03.000 --> 00:27:13.000
a couple of others went down to the bus station I think it was and got arrested.

00:27:13.000 --> 00:27:25.000
And a game Bob Moses said that we had to support these kids and we also could use the PR like we leave them in for certain amount of time.

00:27:25.000 --> 00:27:30.000
And then we'd bail them out because we could use the PR and stuff.

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:38.000
But Bob Moses said somebody's got to go and make sure that they feel comfortable in jail and this was the first time that they had done that.

00:27:38.000 --> 00:27:44.000
So I got elected to go and visit them in the jail.

00:27:44.000 --> 00:27:48.000
They were down in Magnolia.

00:27:48.000 --> 00:28:06.000
I got together with George Hitz who said as I got in a car as we're driving from Pike County down to Magnolia.

00:28:06.000 --> 00:28:12.000
He pulls out a silver handle pistol and says don't worry about a thing.

00:28:12.000 --> 00:28:15.000
Sit tight.

00:28:15.000 --> 00:28:25.000
So we rode down to Magnolia and I was dressed and one of the things when we started I was snick you were always supposed to be dressed in certain tie.

00:28:25.000 --> 00:28:29.000
You're always supposed to be giving off another kind of image.

00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:38.000
So that day I was into my black suit looking like a lawyer or a minister or whatever and I had my attitude case.

00:28:38.000 --> 00:28:40.000
And it's I never will forget him.

00:28:40.000 --> 00:28:53.000
It's old but tobacco chewing guy was sitting on the sea outside of this the stairwell going up to the stairs and he's and I walked up and he says never what you want.

00:28:53.000 --> 00:29:05.000
And I looked him dead and he I was kind of like he was sitting on this stoop kind of and I was looking him dead in the eye and I says my name is Reginald Robinson.

00:29:05.000 --> 00:29:09.000
I'm a field secretary for the student of the foreign coordinating committee.

00:29:09.000 --> 00:29:17.000
I'm here to see and I pulled out my list and I said here to see Curtis as well.

00:29:17.000 --> 00:29:20.000
Thank you.

00:29:20.000 --> 00:29:23.000
You want them know the niggas.

00:29:23.000 --> 00:29:34.000
I will not let you up in here and I didn't see anything else of any turns and he goes and he opens his first door and a door slams behind me.

00:29:34.000 --> 00:29:39.000
He opens this second door and the door slams behind me.

00:29:39.000 --> 00:29:44.000
We go up these stairs and the door slams behind me.

00:29:44.000 --> 00:30:01.000
We go in and I finally see Curtis and Hollis and they were they I like this and he opens up the cell and he the jail opens up the cell and he lets me in right.

00:30:01.000 --> 00:30:08.000
And so I talked to him and get all the information and cool down and they wonder what the hell I mean.

00:30:08.000 --> 00:30:21.000
And I'm telling them what I'm there for just to give you this support and let you know what they say when I have your black ass go get out of here.

00:30:21.000 --> 00:30:28.000
So when I got got finished interviewing them everything I turned and I said jailer.

00:30:28.000 --> 00:30:31.000
And he came and said what the hell you were.

00:30:31.000 --> 00:30:36.000
This is I'm ready to leave and he opened the door.

00:30:36.000 --> 00:30:47.000
And of course everybody and each door opened and I walked back out and I went back and I made my report that everybody was fine.

00:30:47.000 --> 00:30:57.000
Called into Julian Bond and everything was fine and everybody was going to hang with me at gave my report and everybody was feeling great.

00:30:57.000 --> 00:31:01.000
Well that's just some of the stuff that I had to do.

00:31:01.000 --> 00:31:11.000
And well I was mainly responsible for the people of everybody.

00:31:11.000 --> 00:31:18.000
You know making sure that the vendors were paid and stuff like that.

00:31:18.000 --> 00:31:25.000
Were you able to do this Brenda Travis and the other girls for you and the others so they let you see them?

00:31:25.000 --> 00:31:32.000
No I didn't see them.

00:31:32.000 --> 00:31:37.000
We were giving out where we could.

00:31:37.000 --> 00:31:50.000
Sure.

00:31:50.000 --> 00:32:06.000
Well I'm in first part a lot of these people that I met that was involved in the Civic Interest Group were kids from West Baltimore.

00:32:06.000 --> 00:32:13.000
And of course the white kids were upper class and everything else.

00:32:13.000 --> 00:32:22.000
So I was from East Baltimore so that was kind of a strike one.

00:32:22.000 --> 00:32:36.000
I had to do a little proving of who I was and kind of make ground and make room for myself.

00:32:36.000 --> 00:32:45.000
I met when I met certain people certain things opened up for me.

00:32:45.000 --> 00:32:51.000
The demonstrations in Baltimore were really hilarious.

00:32:51.000 --> 00:32:59.000
I more or less became in charge of like coordinating the activities at some point.

00:32:59.000 --> 00:33:16.000
We had at the height of things when we brought when we made the local restaurant association come into conversation for about a two week period.

00:33:16.000 --> 00:33:26.000
We had three renults that we would pile anywhere from seven to eight people in each renult.

00:33:26.000 --> 00:33:33.000
And at lunchtime go to the biggest restaurants in Baltimore.

00:33:33.000 --> 00:33:38.000
And before being arrested of course they had to read you the Miranda Act.

00:33:38.000 --> 00:33:42.000
So they would come to the police and go and shut down the restaurant.

00:33:42.000 --> 00:33:49.000
The police would walk in and read the Miranda and then if you walk out then you weren't arrested.

00:33:49.000 --> 00:33:53.000
So we would go back and get into the renult and go to another restaurant.

00:33:53.000 --> 00:33:59.000
And the police would go, so we had the police department going, we had the restaurant people throwing all up.

00:33:59.000 --> 00:34:05.000
And so finally the restaurant to us is, let's talk to these crazy people.

00:34:05.000 --> 00:34:17.000
Well of course some of them was getting arrested there also and that's also when the NAACP also said that it was in the public accommodations bill was in the courts.

00:34:17.000 --> 00:34:24.000
And it wasn't necessary for all of this activity to be going on.

00:34:24.000 --> 00:34:28.000
And I'm only going to mention this person's name one time.

00:34:28.000 --> 00:34:34.000
His name is Mr. William "Little Willie" Adams.

00:34:34.000 --> 00:34:46.000
He came to our rescue in terms of helping us with bond because his man, the Dixon bond bailman was under his...

00:34:46.000 --> 00:34:49.000
...privileged, and he came out.

00:34:49.000 --> 00:34:56.000
His wife was also went to the house legislature.

00:34:56.000 --> 00:34:59.000
So he was a very political person.

00:34:59.000 --> 00:35:07.000
And he was the one that continued to support the students and their activities.

00:35:07.000 --> 00:35:10.000
The sit-ins around Baltimore was not...

00:35:10.000 --> 00:35:17.000
...nobody really got tossed around or really done in like they did.

00:35:17.000 --> 00:35:20.000
I mean you got called names and stuff like that.

00:35:20.000 --> 00:35:24.000
I can't recall anybody really getting hurt or really being rough.

00:35:24.000 --> 00:35:31.000
When we got to South Baltimore, we got a little ugly and we got into little Italy, we got a little scared.

00:35:31.000 --> 00:35:44.000
But you know, basically Baltimore was not like going into a lunch counter in McComb or going into a lunch counter in Atlanta.

00:35:44.000 --> 00:35:50.000
When we went into the Peachtree Manor, we'd go with Gingo O'Dingo.

00:35:50.000 --> 00:35:56.000
And they threw us out so it's about the same.

00:35:56.000 --> 00:36:08.000
But Baltimore was...well, Baltimore for me at that point was my stepping ground and how I was going to make it my way.

00:36:08.000 --> 00:36:20.000
And I met and was supported by some very good people when the voter registration activity kind of started.

00:36:20.000 --> 00:36:48.000
The reason I got into a position of treasurer which became a small stipend kind of position because of Mr. Harry, Troy Brailey, Troy Brailey, who was the Union representative, AFL-CIO, Union representative, who just so happens knew my father.

00:36:48.000 --> 00:36:54.000
Just so happens was on this advisory committee to the students.

00:36:54.000 --> 00:37:07.000
But he was one of those people that came around and saw a little clone drink somebody back there and he took me on his wing and showed me some few things.

00:37:07.000 --> 00:37:10.000
And then I wound up being okay.

00:37:10.000 --> 00:37:22.000
There was Miss Oliver, Mrs. Elizabeth Murphy Oliver who was a writer for the Washington, for the (Baltimore) Afro-American newspaper.

00:37:22.000 --> 00:37:46.000
And she was also part of the (Baltimore) Afro-American newspaper family and her daughter, Marcia, were also a big influence in my getting ahead in things because they would introduce me to certain people.

00:37:46.000 --> 00:37:50.000
They would take me to certain parties.

00:37:50.000 --> 00:38:00.000
So once I got involved in intersnick, things began to come around me and come to me that I took advantage of.

00:38:00.000 --> 00:38:14.000
And it all wasn't deal with the demonstrations because I became a worker for the situation.

00:38:14.000 --> 00:38:35.000
And so when the guys called for who was ready to give up school and do this number, this larger number that we were talking about doing, I had no fear about signing on because it felt like I was doing the same thing I was doing in Baltimore.

00:38:35.000 --> 00:38:48.000
Not thinking the fear or the repercussions or whatever, I mean the same repercussions in Baltimore could have been killed, could have been locked up, could have been anything else.

00:38:48.000 --> 00:38:58.000
So Baltimore was the beginning in a lot of ways.

00:38:58.000 --> 00:39:13.000
My dad was proud. My mom, another person I'll mention that helped me a lot was the guy named Larry Steele.

00:39:13.000 --> 00:39:22.000
It used to be a stringer for jet magazine and Ebony. Larry and I became very, very good friends.

00:39:22.000 --> 00:39:30.000
And one of the things that I had to promise my father when I signed on to this was that, of course he was big.

00:39:30.000 --> 00:39:35.000
He said, don't worry about me, we'll call your mom every other week and stuff like that.

00:39:35.000 --> 00:39:47.000
So this relationship with Larry became a lot, Larry on his runs or coming through Baltimore and stuff.

00:39:47.000 --> 00:40:02.000
I would see Larry more than I would talk to my mom. So Larry would stop by and talk to my mom and soothe her about everything was okay and he'd just talk to me and where I was and what I was doing.

00:40:02.000 --> 00:40:24.000
So my mom's was as cool as moms could be. I guess my sister was proud of me. I don't know what my brother really thought of me because I don't think he really understood what I was doing or where I was going or the chances I was taking.

00:40:24.000 --> 00:40:37.000
What I said to him as I left was that if I survive where I'm going, I'm going to be alright the rest of my life.

00:40:37.000 --> 00:40:45.000
And I said it's looking to you today and I'm pretty wealthy.

00:40:45.000 --> 00:40:50.000
You had that foresight about what that was missing?

00:40:50.000 --> 00:41:12.000
No. I didn't have a foresight at that time but I could fit it into what I had already done in Baltimore for about a year and the kinds of games and kinds of stuff I've seen people do and manipulations and activities.

00:41:12.000 --> 00:41:25.000
So when this opportunity came along I said well what the heck? What's the worst can happen? I can make it or not.

00:41:25.000 --> 00:41:54.000
So once we got into the stuff in in in McComb and the kids of course all the other activities that went on and things and then when the kids walked out of school that particular day was the worst day even for us because it really it really brought to mind that they were really down to get us.

00:41:54.000 --> 00:42:04.000
One of the things that they had they had a warrant out a real warrant out for Diane Nash at that particular moment.

00:42:04.000 --> 00:42:18.000
So the night before that everybody was everybody was in town all 16 of us was in town Bob Moses Zona had not gotten into McComb just yet.

00:42:18.000 --> 00:42:35.000
He was still in the line of begging to come in and we and we and McComb begging him not to come in because we we singing and praying because we know we're getting ready to face.

00:42:35.000 --> 00:42:45.000
So finally that night he came on in. So that next day we all up in the office.

00:42:45.000 --> 00:43:00.000
Faintly we hear in the background this sound and it's getting louder and louder and then we we we know what it is.

00:43:00.000 --> 00:43:18.000
So being who we are we've always been prepared for demonstration stuff so we broke open the signs and everything and came down and made assignments and stuff and came down on the street and met the kids and march with them into town because everybody took their positions.

00:43:18.000 --> 00:43:40.000
My position that time was to observe I could get close to enough to see what was going on and then report to you to get to a telephone and and and and in those days to get a telephone you had to go through an operator to get out otherwise.

00:43:40.000 --> 00:43:58.000
So I put the call in before the march started and Julian Bond was holding. I think Charlie Jones was down at Dr. Anderson's house because Dr. Anderson having the only doctor's phone could go straight out.

00:43:58.000 --> 00:44:11.000
So we left Diane Nash in the Masonic temple because we didn't want her to get get caught. Everybody else took up positions and went downtown well by that time you know all hell broke loose.

00:44:11.000 --> 00:44:17.000
They jumped on Bob Moses and they got everybody and me and then things kind of moved back up.

00:44:17.000 --> 00:44:32.000
Bob Moses was on the job jump jump jump jump jump down Bob Moses's on the then then I think Moses covered him and I think make do cover him and a couple of us covered.

00:44:32.000 --> 00:44:43.000
They keep him from killing everyone and they pulled him off and they worked him to more and but anyway we finally got everybody out and back to Wall Street.

00:44:43.000 --> 00:44:53.000
But now in the meantime while everything is going on I'm in I'm upstairs in the Masonic temple looking down.

00:44:53.000 --> 00:44:59.000
The police come by and pick up (Charles) Sherrod and Cordell Reagon.

00:44:59.000 --> 00:45:17.000
In the meantime I see the big sergeant walking up the stairs to the Masonic temple inside the Masonic temple is a guy from Detroit by the name of A.G. Gaston and Diane Nash.

00:45:17.000 --> 00:45:38.000
So I look at this back door and I'm in there all of this stuff is coming to me as this sergeant is big I forget his name but he's a big one and he was coming up the steps and I looked at this black cloth at the back of the Masonic temple.

00:45:38.000 --> 00:45:48.000
I don't know nothing about the Masons, but somehow another I thought that if we got through that black space we would be safe.

00:45:48.000 --> 00:45:59.000
So I told Diane Nash and Gaston come with me we got through the black space and open the door and where we were on the roof.

00:45:59.000 --> 00:46:07.000
But this cop walked all around the Masonic temple all around and went back out.

00:46:07.000 --> 00:46:16.000
I told Gaston that's the job he cool Gaston couldn't wait he got excited he jumped off the roof and they caught him out on a highway.

00:46:17.000 --> 00:46:35.000
Well I got Diane Nash back inside we got on a worked out way on the Wall Street and as I said everybody got together then the decision was to make that this was a little too hot for us and so we could make decisions so we decided to go back to Atlanta.

00:46:35.000 --> 00:46:43.000
That's when we found out the next day the message on the Wall Street snake house snake gun snuck.

00:46:46.000 --> 00:47:00.000
No we never did but we went back to Atlanta and gathered at BB Beaman's and made the decisions of what we were going to do.

00:47:00.000 --> 00:47:08.000
Bob Moses I think it was Bob Moses Moses and Chuck McDew was going back into Mississippi.

00:47:08.000 --> 00:47:14.000
Charlie Jones and and (Charles) Sherrod and Cordell Reagon was going down to Southwest Georgia.

00:47:14.000 --> 00:47:28.000
I was sent up to coordinate on route 50th group 40 with with core and then assignments were made.

00:47:28.000 --> 00:47:36.000
While I'm working out coordinate route 40 with core I get this call from Ruby Doris (Smith) Robinson.

00:47:36.000 --> 00:47:39.000
This is get over to the core office.

00:47:39.000 --> 00:47:56.000
We got a four or five people of ours that just got into the core office saying that they go in somewhere to demonstrate they ain't never demonstrated in their life and baby baby go find out what's going on.

00:47:56.000 --> 00:48:04.000
I go over to the core office there's all of these people from New York.

00:48:04.000 --> 00:48:25.000
There's Faith Holsaert there's I'm probably going to get a blinded kill steam and there's Peggy Dammond, there's Angela Butler.

00:48:25.000 --> 00:48:38.000
And we were joined by Bill Hansen who had just demonstrated in a dappless you didn't come out of New York out of New York and then there was a couple of local ball of mouth folk.

00:48:38.000 --> 00:48:52.000
The intentions was to go to Crisfield, Maryland sit in at the governor and then Governor Tawes restaurant in Crisfield, Maryland.

00:48:52.000 --> 00:48:59.000
This is at Christmas time 61 and they and they knew we're going to get put out.

00:48:59.000 --> 00:49:06.000
I said they had a theme of there was no room in the end.

00:49:06.000 --> 00:49:21.000
So I'm trying to tell them you know are you all ready for this you know what can happen you haven't had any train and what what the only one in the group to hand in was Angela Butler because she was a part of the national group.

00:49:21.000 --> 00:49:25.000
She had been there living in New York.

00:49:25.000 --> 00:49:49.000
Well we get on buses and we go down here we go into Chrisfield and we're going to Governor Tawes as a place they read the Miranda act but they decide that they ain't got trees like they do in ball of war after they read the Miranda act they like that as a job.

00:49:49.000 --> 00:50:04.000
No one no one and this is the first and only time in the six years that I was with snake that I got locked up that's the only time that I ever got locked up.

00:50:04.000 --> 00:50:18.000
Yeah so then we we they take us to Princess Anne, Maryland and then of course overnight and everything and then (Juanita) Mitchell again.

00:50:18.000 --> 00:50:23.000
The Mitchell family becomes our attorneys.

00:50:23.000 --> 00:50:30.000
In the meantime we meet Freddie St. Clair and Walter Black.

00:50:30.000 --> 00:50:36.000
Walter Black from Eastern Maryland and Freddie St. Clair from Cambridge, Maryland.

00:50:36.000 --> 00:50:42.000
They are the bonds, billsments.

00:50:42.000 --> 00:50:47.000
We decide again to stay in the amount of time to get to PR and everything.

00:50:47.000 --> 00:51:02.000
I got out to do PR and went to New York and everywhere and started doing things and and getting raising money and the rest of the stuff that we did when somebody was in and getting bail and everything lawyers and all of that kind of stuff.

00:51:02.000 --> 00:51:07.000
In the meantime I'm I'm knowing Freddie St. Clair.

00:51:07.000 --> 00:51:22.000
So we get everybody out and we all go to New York for Christmas but there's discussion about whether we're going to do about Cambridge or what are we going to do about the Eastern Shore not necessarily Cambridge.

00:51:22.000 --> 00:51:31.000
But we have now this invitation from Freddie St. Clair to come into Cambridge and that they would support us.

00:51:31.000 --> 00:51:45.000
So we discussed this in New York over the holidays and of course we in touch with Atlanta and it's decided that Cambridge we were going to Cambridge and take a look see.

00:51:45.000 --> 00:51:54.000
So that's when they asked Bill Hansen to become a secretary and he went back to Cambridge with me.

00:51:54.000 --> 00:52:15.000
Well first the civic interest group, Nagout of Washington, all of the, all of the, let's put it this way, all of the snake affiliates that was in the area was asked to mobilize and come in on weekends.

00:52:15.000 --> 00:52:20.000
We used to have just weekend demonstrations in Cambridge.

00:52:20.000 --> 00:52:32.000
We continued to do that until the community started doing damage getting involved in the demonstrations.

00:52:32.000 --> 00:52:43.000
Then it became as Cambridge began to grow it became a spot and everybody wanted the spot.

00:52:43.000 --> 00:52:49.000
But again our rule was we build, we grow, we leave.

00:52:49.000 --> 00:52:54.000
Cambridge had a very strong organization.

00:52:54.000 --> 00:53:05.000
Freddie gave up the organization early on because not only Freddie was in business his dad was the funeral director.

00:53:05.000 --> 00:53:16.000
So he was in business so the business became much more important than being chairman of a civic organization where you got to be going to meetings and running around.

00:53:16.000 --> 00:53:24.000
So then his cousin Gloria Richardson steps in.

00:53:24.000 --> 00:53:36.000
Now the same class has got an old history of Cambridge where the great, great granddaddy was the first city councilman or own slaves.

00:53:36.000 --> 00:53:41.000
I don't know something like that, but he was way, way, way, way, way back.

00:53:41.000 --> 00:53:46.000
So when Gloria took over it was another kind of scene.

00:53:46.000 --> 00:53:52.000
So we had somebody that also do something about business and some about organization and stuff.

00:53:52.000 --> 00:54:07.000
So we built some other people around her that the organization became organized enough to deal and negotiate with the national guard and Kennedy and everything else.

00:54:07.000 --> 00:54:16.000
So we began to say, Ruby Doris (Smith) Robinson, I think we need to, you know, back off.

00:54:16.000 --> 00:54:36.000
Well, before we could do that, the white establishment said that they were going to hold a referendum on public accommodations.

00:54:36.000 --> 00:54:48.000
Gloria said that no black folks was going to vote for the referendum.

00:54:48.000 --> 00:54:56.000
I said, you can't do that.

00:54:56.000 --> 00:55:03.000
She said, this is Cambridge.

00:55:03.000 --> 00:55:07.000
I can do anything I want to do.

00:55:07.000 --> 00:55:13.000
I says, no, you can't because you are an affiliate of snake.

00:55:13.000 --> 00:55:20.000
We got people dying in the South for road voter registration. We got people getting locked up.

00:55:20.000 --> 00:55:29.000
We got, how does it look and affiliate up here, advocating no vote when all of this activity is going on?

00:55:29.000 --> 00:55:37.000
She says, well, I run this one. That says, no. You may think you run it.

00:55:37.000 --> 00:55:49.000
So of course, I went back to the board. Now, I went to the board that we had built in Cambridge and explaining what I was saying.

00:55:49.000 --> 00:55:54.000
And they said, of course, we got the vote.

00:55:54.000 --> 00:55:58.000
What was her position? What? And why they shouldn't vote.

00:55:58.000 --> 00:56:07.000
Because there was enough white people to vote for the referendum in order for black folks not to have to vote for it to pass.

00:56:07.000 --> 00:56:16.000
So black folks wasn't necessarily for black folks to participate in order for it to become law.

00:56:16.000 --> 00:56:24.000
Which may or may not have been, there's more registered white folks that that could have happened.

00:56:24.000 --> 00:56:32.000
But the point of it was, we could not stay out of a vote no matter what the outcome would be.

00:56:32.000 --> 00:56:35.000
Whether they were both or not, we couldn't stay out of the vote.

00:56:35.000 --> 00:56:42.000
So of course, that became a vote of contention.

00:56:42.000 --> 00:56:54.000
And then it was sort of, at that point, we were getting ready to have a conference in Atlanta.

00:56:54.000 --> 00:57:09.000
And Ruby asked me to stop it all of the black campuses to build Hanson and I to stop it all of the black campuses.

00:57:09.000 --> 00:57:16.000
Black and white campuses coming down to talk up the conference coming up.

00:57:16.000 --> 00:57:27.000
Now, I worked with Bill Hansen in Cambridge, Maryland.

00:57:27.000 --> 00:57:39.000
And Hanson's white. I've always felt that Hansen was hiding from his own community.

00:57:39.000 --> 00:57:53.000
Because if he was daring enough to do the shit that he did in our community, then I'm quite sure he could have convinced some white folks to come on and understand what was going on.

00:57:53.000 --> 00:58:01.000
He had a very arrogant kind of attitude about the way he would express himself.

00:58:01.000 --> 00:58:07.000
Like when we were in New York, he hadn't even really become a secretary yet.

00:58:07.000 --> 00:58:14.000
But Angela Butler at that time had become a star almost.

00:58:14.000 --> 00:58:19.000
She was on Jack Carson and she had already been in the Juilliard School of Music.

00:58:19.000 --> 00:58:23.000
So she was on her way so they knew people. Peggy was into drama and stuff.

00:58:23.000 --> 00:58:26.000
These kids were going places. So they knew people.

00:58:26.000 --> 00:58:38.000
When we got to New York, we were at a party with people like Godfrey Cambridge and Barbara Tia and even there was Sal Mineo there.

00:58:38.000 --> 00:58:46.000
But at this party, somebody came to me and said, hey man, you got to get your man in check.

00:58:46.000 --> 00:58:50.000
He just caused Sal Mineo to leave.

00:58:50.000 --> 00:58:52.000
I said, what are you talking about?

00:58:52.000 --> 00:58:58.000
The way that he came on to him about what's going on and saying that you got all of it.

00:58:58.000 --> 00:59:06.000
I mean, he was just so rough until he just made the man feel bad and just left.

00:59:06.000 --> 00:59:13.000
Well, when we left New York going back to Cambridge, there was no reason.

00:59:13.000 --> 00:59:20.000
And we're going out at night going into being picked up in the Cambridge at night.

00:59:20.000 --> 00:59:34.000
There was no reason for Bill Hansen to announce or as we getting on the bus going to New York, what we're going, where we going and what we're going to do.

00:59:34.000 --> 00:59:42.000
When we got to Cambridge on these weekend things when we go to the Choptank Inn, the reporters would always come to me saying, hey, red, you're going to New York.

00:59:42.000 --> 00:59:47.000
You're going to the Choptank Inn with Bill Hansen? I say, hell no.

00:59:47.000 --> 00:59:53.000
I said, well, I know. I said, even if the Choptank Inn opened them all, I wouldn't go in there and get nothing.

00:59:53.000 --> 00:59:56.000
Not even going to carry out.

00:59:56.000 --> 01:00:00.000
But if that's what he thinks he needs to do, and that's what he needs to do.

01:00:00.000 --> 01:00:06.000
And he would go in there and get hit upside to here with iron chairs and bottles and get thrown through the windows.

01:00:06.000 --> 01:00:12.000
And each week he would go back and I would tell him, that ain't necessary to do.

01:00:12.000 --> 01:00:16.000
You don't have to do that.

01:00:16.000 --> 01:00:18.000
So we would have these kinds of things.

01:00:18.000 --> 01:00:35.000
So when we got to Virginia Union, Reggie Green, who's now a minister in Washington, DC, said to me, say, baby, if you're going to too many more out of schools, you're going to lose out.

01:00:35.000 --> 01:00:39.000
I said, well, you're talking about it. And then he started talking about how Bill was.

01:00:39.000 --> 01:00:42.000
So and I had been complaining to Ruby.

01:00:42.000 --> 01:00:45.000
So Ruby says, okay, here's what we do. We split you up.

01:00:45.000 --> 01:00:49.000
He goes to the White campuses. You go to the Black campuses.

01:00:49.000 --> 01:00:52.000
So we split up.

01:00:52.000 --> 01:01:03.000
So I then went on to Livingstone College and other colleges to talk up the conference.

01:01:03.000 --> 01:01:12.000
I went from Atlanta to some, I think the guy's name was Johnson or something like that.

01:01:12.000 --> 01:01:17.000
Anyway, he was a young minister. He was a young divinity student.

01:01:17.000 --> 01:01:20.000
He smuggled me on campus.

01:01:20.000 --> 01:01:26.000
And I stayed on campus for maybe about two weeks before they found me.

01:01:27.000 --> 01:01:34.000
I moved around the city and did a report. I'm sorry, we can't find it.

01:01:34.000 --> 01:01:52.000
And I did all of the topographical stuff about the Air Force Academy and what was important was I met 12 ministers and we called them the 12 high.

01:01:52.000 --> 01:01:57.000
I also met (Amelia) (Amelia) Boynton. (Amelia) Boynton, then I was there.

01:01:57.000 --> 01:02:08.000
So I made my report and then I went on to the other colleges and then after our conference in making new assignments,

01:02:08.000 --> 01:02:19.000
it was decided that Bernard Lafayette would go to to to to Selma because of these 12 ministers.

01:02:19.000 --> 01:02:30.000
Because him being a young minister, he would relate better to what we have established as the leadership.

01:02:30.000 --> 01:02:41.000
So him and Colia (Liddell) Lafayette, I think, went on in there and that's when the other activities began to happen.

01:02:42.000 --> 01:02:46.000
And I knew there was a ministerial connect to the cabinet for all these things.

01:02:46.000 --> 01:02:48.000
Yeah, that's how it happened.

01:02:48.000 --> 01:02:50.000
That's how it happened.

01:02:50.000 --> 01:02:55.000
Because we used to hang out at the at the doing call, the chicken chat.

01:02:55.000 --> 01:02:57.000
In Selma.

01:02:57.000 --> 01:03:02.000
And then I sneak back on campus.

01:03:02.000 --> 01:03:05.000
Really go back and ask you a couple things.

01:03:05.000 --> 01:03:13.000
So in the column, you left in Bob Moses's house and you all not wanting him to come and he wanted to come and then he got jumped.

01:03:13.000 --> 01:03:16.000
Not everybody's going to have that picture of Bob Moses's house.

01:03:16.000 --> 01:03:22.000
Can you explain what the issue is with him for people who don't know?

01:03:23.000 --> 01:03:29.000
Well, we weren't we weren't too sure what was going down.

01:03:29.000 --> 01:03:39.000
But we knew that if we knew from other experiences that if we had a white boy up on this march, it was going to be a lot rougher than what it was going to be.

01:03:39.000 --> 01:03:48.000
So we were trying to keep the roughness down.

01:03:49.000 --> 01:03:54.000
But Bob Moses was insisting of course his position is being a part of us.

01:03:54.000 --> 01:03:57.000
And he wanted to be there.

01:03:57.000 --> 01:04:04.000
And we think that we don't quite want to ask this cake this bad.

01:04:04.000 --> 01:04:13.000
And that was the same kind of thing that I go back with Bill Hansen.

01:04:13.000 --> 01:04:18.000
But Bob Moses Zona was far different than a Bill Hansen.

01:04:18.000 --> 01:04:25.000
Bob Moses was a person that was very interested in talking and moving with his community.

01:04:25.000 --> 01:04:28.000
He was not trying to hide.

01:04:28.000 --> 01:04:34.000
And his credentials was much different than Bill Hansen.

01:04:34.000 --> 01:04:37.000
He was not trying to hide.

01:04:37.000 --> 01:04:46.000
But the only thing was that at that time we just felt as though it had been a lot easier on the situation if he did not come.

01:04:46.000 --> 01:04:59.000
But now Bob Moses has been there really pushed the envelope because it aggravated the policeman and they saw this white boy up in there.

01:04:59.000 --> 01:05:04.000
And they just couldn't help themselves.

01:05:05.000 --> 01:05:10.000
Oh yeah they wanted to kill him.

01:05:10.000 --> 01:05:14.000
They wanted to do him in.

01:05:14.000 --> 01:05:17.000
But yeah so that was the only thing.

01:05:17.000 --> 01:05:22.000
We were just trying to keep it from being as rough as it was.

01:05:22.000 --> 01:05:33.000
How did you all view the fact that when you were young people and you go into McComb and then you know it is that we are doing like a month.

01:05:33.000 --> 01:05:40.000
How did you all cope with that?

01:05:40.000 --> 01:05:53.000
Well when we first heard about it that was our first experience with realities of stuff that we had done.

01:05:53.000 --> 01:05:57.000
Our first reaction was to run.

01:05:57.000 --> 01:06:06.000
But then we had a long conversation with Amzie Moore.

01:06:06.000 --> 01:06:22.000
And Amzie Moore pointed out that we wanted to think that we had to do was to show that again that we were not afraid and that we were in support of what we were talking about doing.

01:06:22.000 --> 01:06:28.000
As the same thing was going down and seeing the kids in jail.

01:06:28.000 --> 01:06:40.000
So Amzie suggested that we have that the funeral become a mass meeting and that we do the mass meeting.

01:06:40.000 --> 01:06:50.000
Well Bob Moses and if I remember right Bob Moses and McDew were on the platforms talking.

01:06:50.000 --> 01:06:56.000
Sharrod and Jones were just milling in the crowd.

01:06:56.000 --> 01:07:03.000
I had the assignment of taking a picture of Louis Allen who I didn't know.

01:07:03.000 --> 01:07:12.000
But Dr. Anderson knew and I and Doc I walked with Dr. Anderson until he spotted Allen.

01:07:12.000 --> 01:07:20.000
And then as I pointed to camera to Mr. Allen, Mr. Allen, I almost took my head off but we got to his picture.

01:07:20.000 --> 01:07:26.000
And then later on of course Mr. Allen was killed.

01:07:26.000 --> 01:07:35.000
But our position our first position was of course to run because we were looking at death ourselves.

01:07:35.000 --> 01:07:39.000
But then Amzie convinced us that we had to stay.

01:07:39.000 --> 01:07:43.000
And that was the same kind of position we did.

01:07:43.000 --> 01:07:50.000
I guess when we got together and went back to Atlanta it was so devastating and we were so strong apart.

01:07:50.000 --> 01:07:54.000
We couldn't put ourselves together there in McComb.

01:07:54.000 --> 01:07:57.000
We had to get stretched out.

01:07:57.000 --> 01:08:01.000
And that's when James Forman came into play.

01:08:01.000 --> 01:08:12.000
That's when we really started organizing and and and and Snake became a little more organized.

01:08:12.000 --> 01:08:15.000
I mean we had somebody to answer to.

01:08:15.000 --> 01:08:24.000
I mean even though we would I mean Ruby was was a commando and you could call Ruby and you could get the right connections about doing things.

01:08:24.000 --> 01:08:29.000
You weren't afraid of being well I traveled a lot on my own.

01:08:29.000 --> 01:08:33.000
I wasn't afraid of not ever being connected with my home base.

01:08:33.000 --> 01:08:38.000
I was never afraid of being caught out there and not being covered.

01:08:38.000 --> 01:08:44.000
But then when James Forman came in things started to organize a little better.

01:08:44.000 --> 01:08:48.000
And then you saw yourself moving in a different kind of direction.

01:08:48.000 --> 01:08:53.000
And then I began to be used in different kinds of ways.

01:08:53.000 --> 01:08:56.000
And Ruby was playing that role.

01:08:56.000 --> 01:08:59.000
She's actually doing things right?

01:08:59.000 --> 01:09:01.000
Just about.

01:09:01.000 --> 01:09:07.000
And she said no to watch line and she's giving directions and moving us around and stuff.

01:09:07.000 --> 01:09:08.000
Yeah.

01:09:08.000 --> 01:09:11.000
James Forman, James Forman for me.

01:09:11.000 --> 01:09:14.000
Jim for me of course.

01:09:14.000 --> 01:09:21.000
So people who don't know can you talk about Amzie Moore and you see who he was and who wrote?

01:09:21.000 --> 01:09:27.000
Amzie Moore was an old post office person.

01:09:27.000 --> 01:09:31.000
He was a military, he was first of all he was a military.

01:09:31.000 --> 01:09:34.000
And he was a soldier and he came home.

01:09:34.000 --> 01:09:38.000
Of course all of the stuff that he met in Mississippi he couldn't deal with.

01:09:38.000 --> 01:09:43.000
He was a postal worker and he still wasn't getting satisfaction.

01:09:43.000 --> 01:09:47.000
He became involved with the NAACP.

01:09:47.000 --> 01:09:58.000
He was just a person that continued to try and find his freedom wherever he lived.

01:09:58.000 --> 01:10:08.000
And he was a person who was unafraid of the possibilities of his actions.

01:10:08.000 --> 01:10:13.000
He just went on and did what he thought was necessary to be done.

01:10:13.000 --> 01:10:25.000
And what he did was he hooked up with other people of the same light and began to organize and do things.

01:10:25.000 --> 01:10:36.000
And when the idea of when him and Bob Moses talked and the idea of us coming in and doing things,

01:10:36.000 --> 01:10:48.000
they thought about, you know, Bob Moses of a county might have been a little rougher to get started in than a place like McComb where there was other possibilities and other resources.

01:10:48.000 --> 01:10:58.000
Because all of these guys, Amzie Moore and C.C. Brian and O. Supercool Daddy,

01:10:58.000 --> 01:11:03.000
all of these men within the state knew each other, Aaron Henry and all of these people.

01:11:03.000 --> 01:11:06.000
So we weren't walking into anything new.

01:11:06.000 --> 01:11:09.000
We were walking into something that was already built.

01:11:09.000 --> 01:11:15.000
It just needed a little, I guess, workers.

01:11:15.000 --> 01:11:27.000
And so when Bob Moses went in and then they decided to, that the plan was to go to Mississippi, go to McComb.

01:11:27.000 --> 01:11:43.000
Well, even after that, Amzie continued to be an advisor of how to go about doing things and where to go and what to do and what to say and just gave us the skinny on Mississippi.

01:11:43.000 --> 01:11:50.000
And how to conduct yourself and how to protect yourself.

01:11:50.000 --> 01:11:54.000
And he was a tall man.

01:11:54.000 --> 01:12:01.000
I know that he mentioned you were the first person you joined by a lawyer in the town.

01:12:01.000 --> 01:12:03.000
Am I remembering that?

01:12:03.000 --> 01:12:06.000
How do you always say that?

01:12:06.000 --> 01:12:09.000
Are you saying that at one point a bomb?

01:12:09.000 --> 01:12:12.000
Later on after we left.

01:12:12.000 --> 01:12:15.000
I think it was after we left.

01:12:15.000 --> 01:12:17.000
I know because I was gone.

01:12:17.000 --> 01:12:20.000
I was gone then.

01:12:20.000 --> 01:12:29.000
You've already described that you were involved in the sitting and the balls more and also about the registration.

01:12:29.000 --> 01:12:33.000
And you mentioned Snickers debating the school in that summer of 16 years.

01:12:33.000 --> 01:12:38.000
Can you talk about what that debate was about and what you thought?

01:12:38.000 --> 01:12:51.000
Well, at the time I wasn't too sure as to what the debate was all about.

01:12:51.000 --> 01:13:07.000
Because as I looked at direct action, we were going into lunch counters and other places going into stores trying to close and being more direct about what we're saying is not happening.

01:13:08.000 --> 01:13:19.000
Well, in the same sense that if you dealing with voter registration and you attempt to register the vote, they're going to hit you in the head.

01:13:19.000 --> 01:13:25.000
So I don't know how more direct than that gets.

01:13:25.000 --> 01:13:35.000
So I didn't really see the difference in whether I was operating on voter registration or operating on direct action.

01:13:35.000 --> 01:13:51.000
When we were in, when I had left McComb and started dealing with Cambridge, Cambridge was more dealing with accommodations and direct action.

01:13:51.000 --> 01:14:04.000
But it was a lot more intense than what I was doing in Mississippi because I didn't have to put up with the National Guard in Mississippi.

01:14:04.000 --> 01:14:08.000
That was somebody else that had to deal with that in Mississippi.

01:14:08.000 --> 01:14:20.000
But in confronting Bobby Kennedy in Mississippi was the same as Confront and Bobby Kennedy in McComb and in Cambridge, Maryland.

01:14:21.000 --> 01:14:35.000
Where in Cambridge, Maryland, after a meeting, he told me he says he was handing out there was a little PT 9 votes that his brother used to run.

01:14:35.000 --> 01:14:42.000
They were tire clips, right? So he said to me, he says, I would give you one, but you know where I tie.

01:14:42.000 --> 01:14:49.000
I said, well, your wife folks been hanging me long enough. I ain't go anywhere no tie for you to get me.

01:14:49.000 --> 01:14:57.000
And he turned red, of course. But you know, he says, I remember John Doar talking about you from Mississippi.

01:14:57.000 --> 01:15:02.000
I said, well, that's all I am. We meet again.

01:15:02.000 --> 01:15:06.000
And well, this time we met in person when it was in Cambridge.

01:15:06.000 --> 01:15:11.000
But he had heard about me in McComb through John Doar.

01:15:11.000 --> 01:15:31.000
Well, one night in Mississippi, Bob Moses had taken this guy down to register the vote and then he didn't register, but we needed an affidavit.

01:15:32.000 --> 01:15:39.000
So we had to go out to his house to get the affidavit.

01:15:39.000 --> 01:15:52.000
There was Bob Moses Moses, John Doar, (Marion) Barry Barry, and me, and George Heads.

01:15:52.000 --> 01:16:04.000
We went out to this guy's house in this open field. And George says, of course, you're all wait till I give the word that I got him, that he comes out.

01:16:04.000 --> 01:16:11.000
Because the old man was sitting there with his shotguns, and when he realized who we were, he cut the light on.

01:16:11.000 --> 01:16:14.000
You've been in Mississippi.

01:16:14.000 --> 01:16:17.000
You know, when there's ain't nothing to wreck, just like this.

01:16:17.000 --> 01:16:22.000
There's one of these up over top of you, and you sitting in a nothing out there with darkness.

01:16:22.000 --> 01:16:33.000
We sat there and talked with this man for, I don't know, how many hours to convince him to give us an affidavit.

01:16:33.000 --> 01:16:43.000
One of the things that the man said to me, said to us was, I'm really afraid because you never know what these white folks are going to do.

01:16:43.000 --> 01:16:55.000
You never know where they are. They might be out there in the darkness, or you go out there to your cow, and they turn green and they jump on you.

01:16:55.000 --> 01:17:06.000
Well, for years, (Marion) Barry and I, every time we would see each other, we would greet each other with, watch out to the white folks, my turn green.

01:17:07.000 --> 01:17:17.000
But to just demonstrate between Mississippi and Cambridge, I mean, I was still dealing with the Justice Department in one hand.

01:17:17.000 --> 01:17:29.000
And then another story about John Doar was when John Hardy, who was the second person that came into Mississippi, came into work with Bob Moses.

01:17:30.000 --> 01:17:38.000
There were some people down in Walthall, and he went to work with the people in Walthall, and he got locked up.

01:17:38.000 --> 01:17:42.000
Well, they beat John pretty bad.

01:17:42.000 --> 01:17:58.000
And when John saw John Doar coming into the cell block or somewhere, he kind of reached out for him, and John Doar kind of gave the hint about, you don't know me.

01:17:59.000 --> 01:18:07.000
And then later on, of course, John spoke with him and got whatever necessary.

01:18:07.000 --> 01:18:16.000
But John Hardy was very, very hurt that he was snubbed by John. Well, John Doar became a good friend, I mean, over the years.

01:18:17.000 --> 01:18:40.000
We did a lot of stuff together, even showed up in Cambridge again, because when things got hot, there was a guy in the Justice Department by the name of Hubbard that went to school with Pop Herb, and Pop Herb St. Clair went to Lincoln University.

01:18:40.000 --> 01:18:55.000
And Hubbard was in the Justice Department, and so John Doar brought Mr. Hubbard in to Cambridge to talk to Pop Herb to see if we could get things calm down.

01:18:55.000 --> 01:19:05.000
And if you know Pop Herb, every second word Pop Herb was, you pig fucker.

01:19:06.000 --> 01:19:18.000
So we had relationships with the Justice Department in different kinds of ways.

01:19:18.000 --> 01:19:28.000
So the work in Mississippi and the work in Maryland didn't differ but so much.

01:19:31.000 --> 01:19:39.000
But I guess, well, it both had the same dangers, as it always had.

01:19:39.000 --> 01:19:50.000
And anyway, when the voter education project came out, the YEP project came out.

01:19:50.000 --> 01:20:06.000
Well, I had worked a couple other projects before this, but after Mississippi and Alabama and everybody got the money, there was a little penny piece of money left for a project in Orangeburg, South Carolina.

01:20:06.000 --> 01:20:13.000
So we had been wanting to get back in Orangeburg to check it out and see what's going on.

01:20:13.000 --> 01:20:25.000
But the people of Orangeburg, the NAACP and all of the adult folks saying, we don't want none of them to sneak people in here.

01:20:25.000 --> 01:20:30.000
And this is before Cleveland gets shot and everything else. We don't want it.

01:20:30.000 --> 01:20:46.000
But they said, and Randolph Blackwell, who was working with YEP at the time, who was also a professor in the HBC kind of situation.

01:20:46.000 --> 01:21:09.000
He got together, I think, with Dr. Thomas at State, South Carolina State, and then they worked out a situation where I would come in, and would be doing, would take the voter registration list that they had.

01:21:09.000 --> 01:21:34.000
And the captains that they had in their organization and make a, put the captains with people, the voting people in the list so that on Election Day, this captain would have known everybody that votes before computers.

01:21:34.000 --> 01:21:44.000
So this captain would know everybody in his precinct, and then these people would be broken down in precinct, and these are your eligible voters.

01:21:44.000 --> 01:21:53.000
So they promised that we would come in and do that and do that only.

01:21:54.000 --> 01:22:06.000
And they also wanted the money to come in from VEP, also, because State would get a little piece of it, and they would see if we would get a little piece of it.

01:22:06.000 --> 01:22:11.000
But they had to take us in this thing.

01:22:11.000 --> 01:22:31.000
So I had, I wanted to go on all over the state before I could get this job done, and even go down to Charleston, South Carolina, to talk to the president, Mr. Charlie Brown, and all the people of the NAACP of Orangeburg, and their advisory council.

01:22:32.000 --> 01:22:40.000
I mean, it was just a hard part of stuff. So we set up this little house, and we started going to work.

01:22:40.000 --> 01:22:46.000
But of course, I recruited a couple of students to come over and help out.

01:22:46.000 --> 01:22:53.000
And in the meantime, I found out that there was a problem with the cafeteria.

01:22:53.000 --> 01:23:02.000
And at the time, there was a guy named Pete Bryant, who was our representative from South Carolina to SNCC.

01:23:02.000 --> 01:23:08.000
And of course, I mean, I couldn't be a SNCC representative in town without conversing with Pete.

01:23:08.000 --> 01:23:13.000
I was never seen on a Claflin campus, or a state's campus.

01:23:13.000 --> 01:23:18.000
I could go to a state's campus because I could meet with Dr. Thomas.

01:23:18.000 --> 01:23:26.000
But I couldn't be seen on Claflin's campus because there was nobody I was supposed to be seeing there.

01:23:26.000 --> 01:23:37.000
But one day, somehow another of the cafeteria just broke out, and somehow another of the other demonstration that I was not even in town.

01:23:37.000 --> 01:23:44.000
So I was nowhere in sight, nowhere around.

01:23:44.000 --> 01:23:48.000
Came back a couple days later, but anyway.

01:23:48.000 --> 01:23:51.000
So those are just some of the things.

01:23:51.000 --> 01:23:59.000
And then I hooked up with, they sent me in to work with the Northern Student Movement.

01:23:59.000 --> 01:24:04.000
Dottie Burlage had a project in Raleigh out of the Northern Student Movement.

01:24:04.000 --> 01:24:13.000
And they sent me in to kind of support her on her situation.

01:24:13.000 --> 01:24:20.000
Jane Stembridge, I knew her for a very short period of time.

01:24:20.000 --> 01:24:22.000
But she came later.

01:24:22.000 --> 01:24:24.000
She came later.

01:24:24.000 --> 01:24:26.000
Ash.

01:24:26.000 --> 01:24:31.000
You mentioned the National Guard in Cambridge.

01:24:31.000 --> 01:24:36.000
Can you talk about what they were doing in there and how that worked?

01:24:36.000 --> 01:24:50.000
Well, by the time the city, the local folk took over,

01:24:50.000 --> 01:24:55.000
they had really closed the town down.

01:24:55.000 --> 01:25:03.000
And I think the mayor of the city got terribly upset.

01:25:03.000 --> 01:25:13.000
And he felt as though the state police was not doing what it was supposed to be doing, pardon me.

01:25:13.000 --> 01:25:20.000
And of course, being the eastern shore of Maryland,

01:25:20.000 --> 01:25:26.000
and the Tawes and all of the water men,

01:25:26.000 --> 01:25:31.000
the eastern shore has a very big influence on the state of Maryland.

01:25:31.000 --> 01:25:36.000
So then it was decided that I guess it was getting completely on a hand

01:25:36.000 --> 01:25:42.000
that they would send in the National Guard to squal this situation.

01:25:42.000 --> 01:25:48.000
Well, they sent in a general by the name of George Gelston.

01:25:48.000 --> 01:25:55.000
And George became an ally.

01:25:55.000 --> 01:26:03.000
Because we would have meetings, me, him, Gloria, Fred Weisgal,

01:26:03.000 --> 01:26:05.000
who was one of our lawyers.

01:26:05.000 --> 01:26:10.000
We would have meetings in Baltimore at Fred Weisgal's house about strategies

01:26:10.000 --> 01:26:15.000
of what we were going to do.

01:26:15.000 --> 01:26:21.000
The guard was in there for to squal things.

01:26:21.000 --> 01:26:28.000
And I kept telling George that that was not going to do it.

01:26:28.000 --> 01:26:32.000
That was only going to make things worse.

01:26:32.000 --> 01:26:37.000
One of the things that happened between George and I

01:26:37.000 --> 01:26:42.000
was that after we got up some kind of relationship,

01:26:42.000 --> 01:26:46.000
he said to me, you know, you're a very interesting person.

01:26:46.000 --> 01:26:50.000
I like to have you as an officer.

01:26:50.000 --> 01:26:54.000
As a George, I can't be no officer.

01:26:54.000 --> 01:26:56.000
I can't even be in your arm.

01:26:56.000 --> 01:26:59.000
And he says, oh, come on. What did you talk about?

01:26:59.000 --> 01:27:02.000
He says, what's your status?

01:27:02.000 --> 01:27:04.000
I said, we need my status.

01:27:04.000 --> 01:27:07.000
I said, I'm four F.

01:27:07.000 --> 01:27:10.000
Is it you four F?

01:27:10.000 --> 01:27:13.000
I said, yep.

01:27:13.000 --> 01:27:16.000
I said, I'm mentally incompetent.

01:27:16.000 --> 01:27:18.000
He says, come on.

01:27:18.000 --> 01:27:23.000
You know, he's talking to the adjective general of the national,

01:27:23.000 --> 01:27:26.000
oh, Merle National God.

01:27:26.000 --> 01:27:29.000
He says, you know, I can check you out.

01:27:29.000 --> 01:27:33.000
That's your prerogative to do that.

01:27:33.000 --> 01:27:36.000
Four F. So he let it go.

01:27:36.000 --> 01:27:43.000
So a few minutes later, he says, you did that, didn't you?

01:27:43.000 --> 01:27:45.000
I said, well, I did what?

01:27:45.000 --> 01:27:48.000
He says, you are really four F.

01:27:48.000 --> 01:27:51.000
And you're mentally incompetent.

01:27:51.000 --> 01:27:55.000
I said, well, I told you. You didn't believe me.

01:27:55.000 --> 01:28:00.000
He says, if you don't mind, could you tell me what happened?

01:28:00.000 --> 01:28:04.000
I said, well, I went down to your army.

01:28:04.000 --> 01:28:06.000
And there was this sergeant.

01:28:06.000 --> 01:28:09.000
And this sergeant put these boards up in front of me.

01:28:09.000 --> 01:28:11.000
And he said, these are inkplots.

01:28:11.000 --> 01:28:13.000
Tell me what you see.

01:28:13.000 --> 01:28:15.000
I said, inkplots.

01:28:15.000 --> 01:28:18.000
The sergeant said, no, you look at them.

01:28:18.000 --> 01:28:20.000
And these are inkplots.

01:28:20.000 --> 01:28:21.000
You look at them.

01:28:21.000 --> 01:28:23.000
And you see something in them.

01:28:23.000 --> 01:28:25.000
Tell me what you see.

01:28:25.000 --> 01:28:28.000
I said, I see inkplots.

01:28:28.000 --> 01:28:31.000
So the sergeant says, no, you don't understand.

01:28:31.000 --> 01:28:32.000
I said, yes, I do.

01:28:32.000 --> 01:28:36.000
If I'm going to be in your army and you tell me that they inkplots,

01:28:36.000 --> 01:28:40.000
I'm going to bleed that they inkplots.

01:28:40.000 --> 01:28:43.000
Incompetent.

01:28:43.000 --> 01:28:46.000
Joseph said.

01:28:46.000 --> 01:28:51.000
So Joseph said, I don't know how you did it, but I didn't.

01:28:51.000 --> 01:28:55.000
Well, let's go pass that, George.

01:28:56.000 --> 01:29:02.000
So we would do things like, George would say,

01:29:02.000 --> 01:29:05.000
Rich, don't have the demonstration this time.

01:29:05.000 --> 01:29:09.000
I said, George, I got to, we pushed against the wall.

01:29:09.000 --> 01:29:14.000
He says, well, if you got to do it, let's go down to this certain point.

01:29:14.000 --> 01:29:17.000
You kneel and pray.

01:29:17.000 --> 01:29:21.000
And then I hold my boys off.

01:29:21.000 --> 01:29:25.000
You kneel and do your little thing and then you go on back.

01:29:25.000 --> 01:29:28.000
We did that a couple of times, right?

01:29:28.000 --> 01:29:31.000
And things went well.

01:29:31.000 --> 01:29:37.000
But one time we did it, and George was out of town.

01:29:37.000 --> 01:29:47.000
His next in charge was Colonel Tawes, the nephew of the governor.

01:29:48.000 --> 01:29:55.000
We get to the point where we're going to stop and pray.

01:29:55.000 --> 01:30:06.000
Cliff Voss, one of our most distinguished people,

01:30:06.000 --> 01:30:14.000
decided that he's going to charge these young white, fixed banets,

01:30:14.000 --> 01:30:19.000
Eastern Shore crackers.

01:30:19.000 --> 01:30:24.000
They grab him and go stab him or hell breaks loose.

01:30:24.000 --> 01:30:31.000
They shoot tear gas, muster gas that night, all over the town,

01:30:31.000 --> 01:30:38.000
especially the black town, black section of town, all over everywhere.

01:30:38.000 --> 01:30:44.000
So of course, Courtland, Stokely and several other people got arrested that night.

01:30:44.000 --> 01:30:49.000
I was helping people with the Denny lines as a picture of me helping a couple of people

01:30:49.000 --> 01:30:52.000
who got shot with canisters.

01:30:52.000 --> 01:30:57.000
But anyway, I then went and went with the doctor and finally got Stokely

01:30:57.000 --> 01:31:03.000
and everybody out of jail and things settled down again.

01:31:03.000 --> 01:31:08.000
And then we went into negotiations again with the National Guard.

01:31:08.000 --> 01:31:16.000
We negotiated on a basis that there was no blacks in the National Guard

01:31:16.000 --> 01:31:20.000
and there was an offensive kind of attitude towards them.

01:31:20.000 --> 01:31:28.000
So a few weeks after that, then this guy named Boxer came, I think he was a Colonel.

01:31:28.000 --> 01:31:32.000
He came down as Georgia's second in the command.

01:31:32.000 --> 01:31:34.000
He was a black guy out of Baltimore.

01:31:34.000 --> 01:31:38.000
So then they integrated to the National Guard.

01:31:38.000 --> 01:31:48.000
So then the National Guard became set back as an observer of the negotiating team.

01:31:48.000 --> 01:31:53.000
And we began to negotiate with the city and with the National Guard.

01:31:53.000 --> 01:31:59.000
That's when Bobby Kennedy started coming in a little more.

01:31:59.000 --> 01:32:04.000
And so that's my estimation of George.

01:32:04.000 --> 01:32:10.000
But George played a very vital role in keeping things together.

01:32:10.000 --> 01:32:17.000
Because before he came in, there was going to be a clash between the black and white community.

01:32:17.000 --> 01:32:24.000
And everybody knows that everybody down there is a hunter.

01:32:24.000 --> 01:32:29.000
And so nobody was really afraid of nobody down there.

01:32:29.000 --> 01:32:34.000
Once the word was out.

01:32:34.000 --> 01:32:38.000
And it was very difficult to keep a cap on things.

01:32:38.000 --> 01:32:46.000
Because at one point in time, there was this open field that buttressed the black and white community.

01:32:46.000 --> 01:32:53.000
And one night, the white folks was trying to come across the field and open fire.

01:32:53.000 --> 01:32:57.000
And then the fire was returned and you didn't have that no more.

01:32:57.000 --> 01:33:03.000
One night, you could hear the car start as it came around racetrack and started at the end.

01:33:03.000 --> 01:33:07.000
And raced up the street and shot you could hear shots going off.

01:33:07.000 --> 01:33:10.000
And it goes up and you could hear it spin around.

01:33:10.000 --> 01:33:14.000
And as it came back, it came back.

01:33:14.000 --> 01:33:19.000
You could hear it open fire, but you heard fire return.

01:33:19.000 --> 01:33:23.000
You could hear that motor going on out of town.

01:33:23.000 --> 01:33:28.000
So it was becoming very, very dangerous.

01:33:28.000 --> 01:33:34.000
Because there was nothing in between to stop.

01:33:34.000 --> 01:33:43.000
That's from really happening, except that the guard was there to hold back the situation which allowed that talking to happen.

01:33:43.000 --> 01:33:51.000
At that time, and also in Cambridge, we made a lot of promises and a lot of slow down on things.

01:33:51.000 --> 01:33:57.000
Because I'm not criticizing Robert C. Weaver, who was at the HUD department.

01:33:57.000 --> 01:34:01.000
But a lot of promises were made that was going to come into Cambridge.

01:34:01.000 --> 01:34:06.000
Gloria was made a lot of promises of things that was going to happen.

01:34:06.000 --> 01:34:10.000
That I don't even know whether they've happened today.

01:34:10.000 --> 01:34:13.000
But they did give a lot of concession.

01:34:13.000 --> 01:34:18.000
And the community still is a very strong community.

01:34:18.000 --> 01:34:24.000
And that was our purpose was to leave a strong community.

01:34:24.000 --> 01:34:34.000
I heard people saying that Cambridge in many ways was more like organizing in the North after the voting rights that,

01:34:34.000 --> 01:34:40.000
you know, the issues were more like the ones that happened later.

01:34:40.000 --> 01:34:42.000
Does that make sense to you?

01:34:42.000 --> 01:34:45.000
You know, there was more like about jobs and access.

01:34:45.000 --> 01:34:48.000
Well, that's where it came from from the beginning.

01:34:48.000 --> 01:34:53.000
I mean, it was sort of like the March on Washington about jobs.

01:34:53.000 --> 01:34:56.000
I mean, jobs were leaving from down there.

01:34:56.000 --> 01:35:01.000
Folks had to go as far away as Delaware at the work.

01:35:01.000 --> 01:35:05.000
There was several factories that had closed the Campbell factory.

01:35:05.000 --> 01:35:09.000
It closed down there.

01:35:09.000 --> 01:35:13.000
And the watermen were not really functioning.

01:35:13.000 --> 01:35:18.000
I mean, and black watermen were making a lot of money.

01:35:18.000 --> 01:35:23.000
And so the job situation was poor.

01:35:23.000 --> 01:35:28.000
The school situation was terrible.

01:35:28.000 --> 01:35:35.000
And everything that you could probably name would be in the mix.

01:35:35.000 --> 01:35:36.000
Yeah.

01:35:36.000 --> 01:35:38.000
He talked about this a little bit.

01:35:38.000 --> 01:35:40.000
Can you describe what kind of person was it?

01:35:40.000 --> 01:35:43.000
Is this the way or the kind of leader?

01:35:43.000 --> 01:35:50.000
Gloria was...

01:35:50.000 --> 01:35:59.000
I don't want to say chrismatically to her.

01:35:59.000 --> 01:36:09.000
But she followed orders to a certain degree in the beginning.

01:36:09.000 --> 01:36:19.000
She had a sense of leadership coming from the people.

01:36:19.000 --> 01:36:24.000
As far as I knew she was listening to what was demands coming out of her board.

01:36:24.000 --> 01:36:27.000
Because she would meet with her board.

01:36:27.000 --> 01:36:32.000
And her board would give her directions as to what to go on.

01:36:32.000 --> 01:36:42.000
But then somewhere in this life, I guess she took on another kind of thing

01:36:42.000 --> 01:36:51.000
when she started running with people like Jessie, Jessie out of New York.

01:36:51.000 --> 01:36:54.000
I can't think of Jesse's name.

01:36:54.000 --> 01:36:57.000
But the whole act group.

01:36:57.000 --> 01:37:02.000
And she earned her name correctly.

01:37:02.000 --> 01:37:10.000
And I think she's in recent years.

01:37:10.000 --> 01:37:18.000
She's may have gotten a few things out of kilter.

01:37:18.000 --> 01:37:24.000
But I think without her taking over from her cousin.

01:37:24.000 --> 01:37:28.000
And the name of St. Clair being what it was.

01:37:28.000 --> 01:37:34.000
That's what made the Cambridge movement what it was.

01:37:34.000 --> 01:37:43.000
And she deserves every bit of accolades and support for her activities

01:37:43.000 --> 01:37:50.000
for building such an organization.

01:37:50.000 --> 01:37:56.000
And she was a very talented person.

01:37:56.000 --> 01:38:02.000
But can you say more about what the position was of the NW-2P?

01:38:02.000 --> 01:38:05.000
Well, that was very basic.

01:38:05.000 --> 01:38:11.000
Because once we had gone and sat in and we had a number of cases in court.

01:38:11.000 --> 01:38:17.000
The air position was, we got this in court the same as what the air position has always been.

01:38:17.000 --> 01:38:19.000
We got this in court now.

01:38:19.000 --> 01:38:25.000
So there's no need of spending any money of your kids going out there doing these things

01:38:25.000 --> 01:38:28.000
and making us spend money to get you out of jail.

01:38:28.000 --> 01:38:34.000
Well, our position was we had to push the envelope because you've been sitting on the court action.

01:38:34.000 --> 01:38:38.000
And if the court action ain't happening then some kind of action has got to happen

01:38:38.000 --> 01:38:41.000
to make the court action happen.

01:38:41.000 --> 01:38:44.000
So we said we're going to go ahead on.

01:38:44.000 --> 01:38:49.000
So I would imagine that they thought that we were finished.

01:38:49.000 --> 01:38:55.000
And then Henry G. Parks Jr came along and gave us life again.

01:38:55.000 --> 01:38:58.000
And then the others support us came along.

01:38:58.000 --> 01:39:03.000
And we began to move again and we were able to do the things that we were doing.

01:39:03.000 --> 01:39:13.000
But as I said, in the beginning I didn't know that what we were doing was building clarences.

01:39:13.000 --> 01:39:16.000
And then the people were like, what?

01:39:16.000 --> 01:39:19.000
And to run back there then.

01:39:19.000 --> 01:39:23.000
But that was the first part of the voter registration activity.

01:39:23.000 --> 01:39:25.000
Then it spread it out.

01:39:25.000 --> 01:39:27.000
When did you run?

01:39:27.000 --> 01:39:33.000
I forgot. I think it was at 60, 63, 62 somewhere around and there.

01:39:33.000 --> 01:39:36.000
That early, yeah.

01:39:36.000 --> 01:39:41.000
You know, I'm a college part of that football.

01:39:41.000 --> 01:39:42.000
So you knew that?

01:39:42.000 --> 01:39:43.000
Yeah.

01:39:43.000 --> 01:39:44.000
Yeah.

01:39:44.000 --> 01:39:47.000
How was she when she went from that school to the New Golfing?

01:39:47.000 --> 01:39:54.000
Well, I had a little something to do with it.

01:39:54.000 --> 01:40:02.000
Of course, when the group came back to Baltimore for a meeting,

01:40:02.000 --> 01:40:04.000
that's when they start meeting everybody.

01:40:04.000 --> 01:40:08.000
And that's when normal met folks.

01:40:08.000 --> 01:40:14.000
And normal began to find her way to do things.

01:40:14.000 --> 01:40:19.000
And then normal sign going to go to Atlanta to work.

01:40:19.000 --> 01:40:23.000
And for I know it, she was in.

01:40:23.000 --> 01:40:24.000
Yeah.

01:40:24.000 --> 01:40:26.000
And Roland.

01:40:26.000 --> 01:40:27.000
Yeah.

01:40:28.000 --> 01:40:36.000
I think really I thought we did early memories of him and the former and maybe John Hardy.

01:40:36.000 --> 01:40:41.000
And that they could all barely fit at the same time in the office.

01:40:41.000 --> 01:40:42.000
Mm-hmm.

01:40:42.000 --> 01:40:43.000
So that's how I...

01:40:43.000 --> 01:40:44.000
Yeah, it's end-ranked.

01:40:44.000 --> 01:40:45.000
Yeah.

01:40:45.000 --> 01:40:46.000
It's end-ranked.

01:40:46.000 --> 01:40:47.000
Yeah.

01:40:47.000 --> 01:40:49.000
It was a very small office.

01:40:49.000 --> 01:40:59.000
But she come out of Morgan.

01:40:59.000 --> 01:41:12.000
I don't know when the normal came out of Morgan or not, but I don't know exactly.

01:41:12.000 --> 01:41:15.000
All I remember was that she was...

01:41:16.000 --> 01:41:20.000
She was like secretary to Clarence Logan, who we call Clarence Logan.

01:41:20.000 --> 01:41:23.000
She was very tight with Clarence...

01:41:23.000 --> 01:41:29.000
Well, the leaders at that time was Clarence Logan and Phil Savage,

01:41:29.000 --> 01:41:32.000
who was hitting the voter registration stuff.

01:41:32.000 --> 01:41:40.000
But then Levin West was the Morgan president.

01:41:40.000 --> 01:41:43.000
Just how normal...

01:41:43.000 --> 01:41:49.000
I think normal came with Clarence Logan.

01:41:49.000 --> 01:41:54.000
And because things became organized once we started doing a voter registration,

01:41:54.000 --> 01:41:57.000
it was records to be kept and things to be done.

01:41:57.000 --> 01:42:03.000
So there was necessary for a secretary at that time.

01:42:03.000 --> 01:42:05.000
Did you know August Meier?

01:42:05.000 --> 01:42:06.000
Yes.

01:42:06.000 --> 01:42:09.000
Yes, I knew August Meier.

01:42:09.000 --> 01:42:14.000
I think I had a bunch of papers over there, so it's Chambler.

01:42:14.000 --> 01:42:18.000
If you could read it in hand right, you can always note.

01:42:18.000 --> 01:42:20.000
Yes, I was at his funeral.

01:42:20.000 --> 01:42:21.000
Oh, yeah?

01:42:21.000 --> 01:42:22.000
Yeah.

01:42:22.000 --> 01:42:28.000
Chambler, he played a role in a vibe in some of his films.

01:42:28.000 --> 01:42:31.000
Well, he was one of...

01:42:31.000 --> 01:42:33.000
He was one of the people that was...

01:42:33.000 --> 01:42:38.000
I would say there was a party advisory group.

01:42:38.000 --> 01:42:41.000
There was an adult group.

01:42:41.000 --> 01:42:44.000
There was an adult group.

01:42:44.000 --> 01:42:47.000
There was a touch to Snake.

01:42:47.000 --> 01:42:59.000
And August Meier being a teacher out at Morgan was close to the students.

01:42:59.000 --> 01:43:05.000
And then there was people like Reverend Bascom.

01:43:05.000 --> 01:43:13.000
