Who was not violent?

01:48:22.000 --> 01:48:24.000
Who wasn't not violent?

01:48:25.000 --> 01:48:33.000
You take a fellow like (Chuck) McDew who comes from Massillon, Ohio.

01:48:33.000 --> 01:48:39.000
You can't really comfort him into nonviolence.

01:48:39.000 --> 01:48:43.000
You might get him to understand a position.

01:48:43.000 --> 01:48:53.000
Now, a Bernard Lafayette with his kind of divinity kind of feeling.

01:48:54.000 --> 01:49:02.000
I guess Absorb with Jim Lawson was saying in such a different manner,

01:49:02.000 --> 01:49:07.000
even though (Chuck) McDew had known also Jim Lawson as well.

01:49:07.000 --> 01:49:10.000
That's right.

01:49:10.000 --> 01:49:19.000
But (Chuck) McDew as a person is a totally different character than Bernard Lafayette.

01:49:19.000 --> 01:49:28.000
But they both could come together under the nonviolent banner and move situations and make things happen.

01:49:28.000 --> 01:49:33.000
You didn't go to the meeting in October six years.

01:49:33.000 --> 01:49:40.000
You know, like just next to the second meeting, that would have been too bad before you had that leadership.

01:49:40.000 --> 01:49:46.000
I didn't get there until I didn't get involved until 61.

01:49:47.000 --> 01:49:52.000
You have a sense of why (Chuck) McDew kept getting real interested as Jim,

01:49:52.000 --> 01:49:58.000
but it was that people were just wanting about him.

01:49:58.000 --> 01:50:09.000
As far as I knew, he had the kind of,

01:50:09.000 --> 01:50:16.000
he had the kind of command of loyalties.

01:50:16.000 --> 01:50:20.000
I mean, when him and I really got to know each other,

01:50:20.000 --> 01:50:24.000
we had certain things in common.

01:50:24.000 --> 01:50:28.000
So I took him on as my chairman.

01:50:28.000 --> 01:50:32.000
And then with me, it was kind of added to this as the chairman,

01:50:32.000 --> 01:50:34.000
he says what goes on.

01:50:34.000 --> 01:50:40.000
The same thing happened with when Jim became the executive director,

01:50:40.000 --> 01:50:46.000
whatever the boss say, do if you got to go and do this.

01:50:46.000 --> 01:50:55.000
But with (Chuck) McDew and I, we became more or less close brothers.

01:51:05.000 --> 01:51:13.000
I really don't know where to go with this one.

01:51:13.000 --> 01:51:15.000
But...

01:51:15.000 --> 01:51:20.000
Probably I was interested because I heard about the competition.

01:51:20.000 --> 01:51:28.000
And some people saying that Nick office was in Atlanta because Nashville got the first chair.

01:51:29.000 --> 01:51:36.000
And then the question about whether Diane Nash Nash should have been chair of Mary and Mary.

01:51:36.000 --> 01:51:42.000
Nick Duce says that he became chair in part because Ella Baker picked him out

01:51:42.000 --> 01:51:45.000
