01:51:45.000 --> 01:51:47.000
And that was the factor.

01:51:47.000 --> 01:51:50.000
Well, that's kind of...

01:51:50.000 --> 01:51:52.000
That's kind of what it was.

01:51:52.000 --> 01:51:54.000
He didn't want it.

01:51:55.000 --> 01:52:02.000
And there was too much competition between the schools being the schools that they are.

01:52:02.000 --> 01:52:05.000
And they became a school competition.

01:52:05.000 --> 01:52:12.000
And that's what Ella saw was this competition between them.

01:52:12.000 --> 01:52:18.000
And nothing was going to happen of what she was talking about us going out and doing.

01:52:18.000 --> 01:52:21.000
But Dew was kind of outside of that.

01:52:22.000 --> 01:52:24.000
And he was not a part of them.

01:52:24.000 --> 01:52:26.000
So he could bring them together.

01:52:26.000 --> 01:52:31.000
So I guess that's always been his explanation about it.

01:52:31.000 --> 01:52:35.000
And he's also kind of been outside of them.

01:52:35.000 --> 01:52:39.000
I mean, he kind of says,

01:52:39.000 --> 01:52:42.000
until I came along,

01:52:42.000 --> 01:52:46.000
I was the only other outsider

01:52:46.000 --> 01:52:50.000
because I didn't come from any of the traditional pieces.

01:52:50.000 --> 01:52:52.000
So he could use me.

01:52:52.000 --> 01:52:58.000
We became allies about things and doing things.

01:52:58.000 --> 01:53:02.000
So yeah, I mean, they had heavy competition going on.

01:53:02.000 --> 01:53:03.000
Heavy.

01:53:03.000 --> 01:53:06.000
So this was because you were trying to think

01:53:06.000 --> 01:53:10.000
out of the first group, the first 16,

01:53:10.000 --> 01:53:15.000
were you in Chuck, the only two that won in the East South?

01:53:15.000 --> 01:53:17.000
Well, Chuck was deep South.

01:53:17.000 --> 01:53:18.000
Chuck was South Carolina.

01:53:18.000 --> 01:53:20.000
I was just thinking about where he grew up.

01:53:20.000 --> 01:53:24.000
Oh, they see who he was.

01:53:36.000 --> 01:53:39.000
I'm kind of thinking who he was.

01:53:39.000 --> 01:53:44.000
Well Paul Brooks was out of Chicago.

01:53:45.000 --> 01:53:48.000
And I think his wife, Gwen,

01:53:48.000 --> 01:53:50.000
was out of Chicago,

01:53:50.000 --> 01:53:52.000
was out of Chicago.

01:53:52.000 --> 01:53:56.000
Diane Nash was out of Chicago.

01:53:56.000 --> 01:53:58.000
Okay.

01:53:58.000 --> 01:54:02.000
Oh, Paul Brooks was like.

01:54:02.000 --> 01:54:10.000
Well, very straightly kind of person.

01:54:11.000 --> 01:54:15.000
Very bad refact and academia,

01:54:15.000 --> 01:54:20.000
you know, one of them kind of straight guys.

01:54:30.000 --> 01:54:38.000
If you can imagine my walking into a hotel conference room

01:54:39.000 --> 01:54:41.000
for the first time,

01:54:41.000 --> 01:54:45.000
and I don't know who they are except for their quick faces,

01:54:45.000 --> 01:54:49.000
but I've seen them in the student voice.

01:54:49.000 --> 01:54:51.000
And there's my seat.

01:54:51.000 --> 01:54:55.000
And my seat is right across from Diane Nash.

01:54:55.000 --> 01:54:58.000
And I'm looking her right straight in the face

01:54:58.000 --> 01:55:01.000
with my patch over my eye.

01:55:01.000 --> 01:55:06.000
And I've never seen such a beautiful woman in it.

01:55:07.000 --> 01:55:09.000
I'm paying more attention to it.

01:55:09.000 --> 01:55:12.000
I ain't paid attention to nobody else around me.

01:55:12.000 --> 01:55:15.000
And later on,

01:55:15.000 --> 01:55:18.000
Connie Curry, after I meet Connie Curry,

01:55:18.000 --> 01:55:21.000
Connie, touched me on the shoulder and says,

01:55:21.000 --> 01:55:24.000
it was a very interesting doodle you had going on there.

01:55:24.000 --> 01:55:26.000
I said, will you mean?

01:55:26.000 --> 01:55:30.000
She says, I saw you doodle in you and Diane Nash.

01:55:30.000 --> 01:55:32.000
And it went to little heart.

01:55:32.000 --> 01:55:35.000
And I hadn't realized I was sitting there doodling.

01:55:35.000 --> 01:55:38.000
I was sitting in the heart and everything.

01:55:38.000 --> 01:55:41.000
And it went when she's just a gorgeous woman.

01:55:41.000 --> 01:55:44.000
So then as I began to meet people

01:55:44.000 --> 01:55:50.000
and understand what their role was and different kinds of ways,

01:55:50.000 --> 01:55:55.000
I began to formulate what I wanted to do.

01:55:55.000 --> 01:55:59.000
Before Ella came out on me because I didn't know how

01:55:59.000 --> 01:56:02.000
which was going to accomplish what I was going to accomplish.

01:56:02.000 --> 01:56:08.000
And then of course when Ella kind of took me in

01:56:08.000 --> 01:56:14.000
and then it became a little more open,

01:56:14.000 --> 01:56:19.000
I began to talk with Diane Nash and we became friends and everything.

01:56:19.000 --> 01:56:25.000
And then it was very interesting when the kids got out of school

01:56:25.000 --> 01:56:28.000
and there was the big warring out on her.

01:56:28.000 --> 01:56:32.000
My responsibility not only of absorbing what was going on

01:56:32.000 --> 01:56:37.000
was to protect Diane Nash and make sure that she didn't get picked up.

01:56:37.000 --> 01:56:43.000
So and then over the years we've been good friends.

01:56:43.000 --> 01:56:51.000
But yes, Diane Nash was, ooh, Lord.

01:56:51.000 --> 01:56:55.000
When a pretty woman ever seen.

01:56:55.000 --> 01:57:00.000
What did you think of the position she took the next summer

01:57:00.000 --> 01:57:04.000
when she was pregnant?

01:57:04.000 --> 01:57:07.000
You know, she was going to jail.

01:57:07.000 --> 01:57:10.000
And the Pacifica can you remember that?

01:57:10.000 --> 01:57:13.000
Oh yeah, well I just thought Diane Nash was just a brave woman.

01:57:13.000 --> 01:57:19.000
I mean, you just go and do anything necessary to be done.

01:57:19.000 --> 01:57:23.000
I mean this is a remarkable woman.

01:57:23.000 --> 01:57:27.000
She also reminded me of another woman that I met in South Carolina

01:57:27.000 --> 01:57:34.000
by a name of Grace Brooks, who was a teacher at South Carolina State,

01:57:34.000 --> 01:57:39.000
was also this same kind of very beautiful

01:57:39.000 --> 01:57:45.000
and Grace finally left South Carolina State

01:57:45.000 --> 01:57:51.000
and joined the Free Southern Theater and acted in that.

01:57:51.000 --> 01:57:59.000
And that was the way she wanted to give to whatever she could do.

01:57:59.000 --> 01:58:06.000
And then there was people that came around like in a typical in a tongue.

01:58:06.000 --> 01:58:07.000
Ooh boy.

01:58:07.000 --> 01:58:09.000
Anyway, she'll come back to me.

01:58:09.000 --> 01:58:13.000
She married Bill Withers.

01:58:13.000 --> 01:58:18.000
She became very, anyway.

01:58:18.000 --> 01:58:21.000
We had some very beautiful women in the movement.

01:58:21.000 --> 01:58:28.000
And I've tried to always support them and whatever it is that they want to do.

01:58:28.000 --> 01:58:34.000
I mean, I didn't want to see Diane Nash go in like that.

01:58:34.000 --> 01:58:41.000
And I never wanted to see her get hurt or any of the sisters to get hurt.

01:58:41.000 --> 01:58:47.000
But if one of the sisters wanted to make a decision about doing something

01:58:47.000 --> 01:58:50.000
they had to back them up.

01:58:50.000 --> 01:58:57.000
Because one of the things that I really learned in the movement

01:58:57.000 --> 01:59:03.000
that there was some very, very, very beautiful strong sisters and beautiful.

01:59:03.000 --> 01:59:08.000
I mean, not only in the facial features of Diane Nash,

01:59:08.000 --> 01:59:12.000
but in all of the other ways that beauty can be a story.

01:59:12.000 --> 01:59:15.000
I mean, Judy is a wonderful person.

01:59:15.000 --> 01:59:23.000
Bobby Yancy, you know, when we first learned how to raise money,

01:59:23.000 --> 01:59:30.000
we put the foil group that made us cry about how you had to do this kind of stuff.

01:59:30.000 --> 01:59:31.000
But she still did it.

01:59:31.000 --> 01:59:33.000
She surely cooks.

01:59:33.000 --> 01:59:40.000
She really write cooks who came down and was working in the movement.

01:59:40.000 --> 01:59:45.000
And of course, there was nobody like Ruby Nars.

01:59:45.000 --> 01:59:48.000
Nobody like Big Mama.

01:59:48.000 --> 01:59:53.000
And then there was Jessie Johnson who took care of us with the money

01:59:53.000 --> 01:59:57.000
and stuff that made sure we were okay.

01:59:57.000 --> 02:00:00.000
It was Connie Curry.

02:00:00.000 --> 02:00:03.000
And Casey Hayden.

02:00:03.000 --> 02:00:07.000
And all of these people were, well, Casey.

02:00:07.000 --> 02:00:12.000
We also thought it was like a movie star.

02:00:12.000 --> 02:00:15.000
Yes, Casey's beautiful gal.

02:00:15.000 --> 02:00:18.000
You think that she must have been married with her friends?

02:00:18.000 --> 02:00:21.000
Oh, yeah.

02:00:21.000 --> 02:00:24.000
Oh, yeah.

02:00:24.000 --> 02:00:31.000
And so the women that came along, you know,

02:00:31.000 --> 02:00:36.000
the gene Will Smiths and the Brenda Travis Travis'

02:00:36.000 --> 02:00:43.000
and Mrs. Cotton who we were talking about.

02:00:43.000 --> 02:00:48.000
Nobody really knew it, but we lived in a whole house.

02:00:48.000 --> 02:00:53.000
I mean, we, well, at the time we didn't know we were in a whole house.

02:00:53.000 --> 02:00:56.000
But we were just anxious.

02:00:56.000 --> 02:00:58.000
We were glad to have someplace to stay.

02:00:58.000 --> 02:01:01.000
And nobody else was ready to take us in.

02:01:02.000 --> 02:01:06.000
Until we got to moving around and meeting people.

02:01:06.000 --> 02:01:11.000
But that was okay.

02:01:11.000 --> 02:01:15.000
Took it, gave us.

02:01:15.000 --> 02:01:20.000
And a lot of places like in Cambridge,

02:01:20.000 --> 02:01:29.000
it wasn't until I'm going to say the underworld.

02:01:31.000 --> 02:01:37.000
It came into, came into understanding what was happening in Cambridge.

02:01:37.000 --> 02:01:40.000
Did the local community really?

02:01:40.000 --> 02:01:44.000
It was the guys that they always been putting in jail

02:01:44.000 --> 02:01:47.000
that started to go on under demonstrations.

02:01:47.000 --> 02:01:52.000
There was the guys at Hungin' a pool room that started to come in out of the pool room.

02:01:52.000 --> 02:01:56.000
So they made the change.

02:01:56.000 --> 02:02:00.000
And then the respectable folks got together and said,

02:02:00.000 --> 02:02:03.000
we were going to go on board,

02:02:03.000 --> 02:02:06.000
because we got to keep things going

02:02:06.000 --> 02:02:09.000
and then things began to operate around.

02:02:09.000 --> 02:02:12.000
But it was the underworld.

02:02:12.000 --> 02:02:15.000
Why do you think they came off first?

02:02:15.000 --> 02:02:18.000
Because they were unafraid.

02:02:18.000 --> 02:02:21.000
They were more unafraid than the rest of these folks,

02:02:21.000 --> 02:02:22.000
or they have to lose.

02:02:22.000 --> 02:02:25.000
They thought they were gaining.

02:02:25.000 --> 02:02:28.000
You think they're happy with how it came off?

02:02:28.000 --> 02:02:31.000
They're going to be able to get to know each other right some time

02:02:31.000 --> 02:02:34.000
and understand there's a few statues around.

02:02:34.000 --> 02:02:37.000
But I don't know how well people are eating.

02:02:37.000 --> 02:02:40.000
I don't know what the housing situation is.

02:02:40.000 --> 02:02:43.000
I don't know whether we own any businesses.

02:02:43.000 --> 02:02:46.000
I don't think Pine Street is up again.

02:02:46.000 --> 02:02:49.000
I mean, there used to be several businesses,

02:02:49.000 --> 02:02:52.000
black businesses on Pine Street.

02:02:52.000 --> 02:02:55.000
I don't know that there's any businesses.

02:02:55.000 --> 02:02:58.000
So I can't say that people are happy.

02:02:58.000 --> 02:03:02.000
I know that people in Mississippi aren't happy.

02:03:02.000 --> 02:03:06.000
I mean, they got more black elected officials

02:03:06.000 --> 02:03:09.000
in Mississippi than any state in the country.

02:03:09.000 --> 02:03:14.000
And it's still a poise state in the country.

02:03:14.000 --> 02:03:20.000
Black folks don't own any production companies.

02:03:20.000 --> 02:03:24.000
I understand Nissan just went back into Canton.

02:03:24.000 --> 02:03:28.000
It seems like, it seems like to me,

02:03:28.000 --> 02:03:34.000
with the types of money that's been reported in the black community.

02:03:34.000 --> 02:03:39.000
It seems like we can get some kind of institution,

02:03:39.000 --> 02:03:43.000
financial institution on a corner

02:03:43.000 --> 02:03:50.000
and start building maybe a laundromat or a general store.

02:03:50.000 --> 02:03:54.000
Everybody ain't got to go out to Walmart.

02:03:54.000 --> 02:03:57.000
I mean, everybody can't get to Walmart.

02:03:57.000 --> 02:04:00.000
I mean, just go back to the old general store,

02:04:00.000 --> 02:04:02.000
have a filling station on a corner,

02:04:02.000 --> 02:04:06.000
have a restaurant where folks can come in

02:04:06.000 --> 02:04:09.000
and off the road or in town.

02:04:09.000 --> 02:04:14.000
And have some kind of institution, financial institution,

02:04:14.000 --> 02:04:18.000
that sits there on that corner, regulates the business,

02:04:18.000 --> 02:04:22.000
make sure that money moves around in that community

02:04:22.000 --> 02:04:24.000
and then moves out.

02:04:24.000 --> 02:04:27.000
I don't understand all the stock exchange and everything,

02:04:27.000 --> 02:04:31.000
but I know that when you got money moving around this week

02:04:31.000 --> 02:04:34.000
and you got money moving over here and coming back to you,

02:04:34.000 --> 02:04:37.000
that you can then go out.

02:04:37.000 --> 02:04:41.000
You can sit at the big poker game and afford to play.

02:04:41.000 --> 02:04:44.000
You can't sit at the poker game.

02:04:44.000 --> 02:04:49.000
If the poker game, if the stakes is $1,000 and you ain't got 25 cents,

02:04:49.000 --> 02:04:53.000
you ain't going to God damn far.

02:04:53.000 --> 02:05:00.000
So I would like to see some of our black businessmen

02:05:00.000 --> 02:05:05.000
take the chance of putting some money together,

02:05:05.000 --> 02:05:10.000
taking one of these small towns,

02:05:10.000 --> 02:05:15.000
putting a financial institution on the corner,

02:05:15.000 --> 02:05:18.000
okay, what you call it?

02:05:18.000 --> 02:05:22.000
But that financial institution will allow you

02:05:22.000 --> 02:05:25.000
to open a laundromat.

02:05:25.000 --> 02:05:28.000
Everybody got to wash the drawers.

02:05:28.000 --> 02:05:34.000
And then I understand that these companies,

02:05:34.000 --> 02:05:41.000
these tools that are used to make computers

02:05:41.000 --> 02:05:48.000
are done in such a fine fashion that you don't need a PhD

02:05:48.000 --> 02:05:50.000
to put the circuits together.

02:05:50.000 --> 02:05:55.000
You just need a little training and you can do a decent job.

02:05:55.000 --> 02:06:00.000
This kind of financial institution could bring in a company

02:06:00.000 --> 02:06:05.000
in a place like Greenwood, Mississippi,

02:06:05.000 --> 02:06:09.000
put up a factory, put up a restaurant,

02:06:09.000 --> 02:06:12.000
put up a laundromat,

02:06:12.000 --> 02:06:15.000
and let that money spin around in that community.

02:06:15.000 --> 02:06:18.000
For you know what you start building houses,

02:06:18.000 --> 02:06:20.000
I ain't got no money.

02:06:20.000 --> 02:06:22.000
If I had some money, I'd do it.

02:06:22.000 --> 02:06:27.000
I ain't had no money since they paid me $9.64.

02:06:27.000 --> 02:06:30.000
I ain't had no money since then.

02:06:30.000 --> 02:06:34.000
It's still ain't got no, but I'm very rich.

02:06:34.000 --> 02:06:37.000
But that's what I would like to see coming out of this

02:06:37.000 --> 02:06:41.000
because we've done all we could with voter registration.

02:06:41.000 --> 02:06:44.000
We've got people hopped up on voter registration

02:06:44.000 --> 02:06:47.000
and for what I can see,

02:06:47.000 --> 02:06:52.000
and it might sound a little awkward,

02:06:52.000 --> 02:06:56.000
but the voter's taking us a little away.

02:06:56.000 --> 02:06:59.000
But we've got to get out there,

02:06:59.000 --> 02:07:05.000
and we've got to find some way to do it economically.

02:07:05.000 --> 02:07:08.000
And then we can control who's in the Congress,

02:07:08.000 --> 02:07:12.000
and we can control who's in the Senate.

02:07:12.000 --> 02:07:15.000
We can back the boys in there,

02:07:15.000 --> 02:07:17.000
and we can then say,

02:07:17.000 --> 02:07:20.000
you don't go back no more if you don't do so.

02:07:20.000 --> 02:07:25.000
We can't do that because we don't pay for them.

02:07:25.000 --> 02:07:29.000
So you were in the federal government,

02:07:29.000 --> 02:07:31.000
and you were in the government?

02:07:31.000 --> 02:07:34.000
I was there for a little while.

02:07:34.000 --> 02:07:37.000
Were you involved in all of the doing the campaign?

02:07:37.000 --> 02:07:43.000
No. I was involved in John's first campaign.

02:07:43.000 --> 02:07:45.000
And you had a good dream?

02:07:45.000 --> 02:07:47.000
Yeah.

02:07:47.000 --> 02:07:49.000
Sorry.

02:07:49.000 --> 02:07:52.000
And the eight and a good lecture.

02:07:52.000 --> 02:07:56.000
I think it was, he ran two times, isn't he?

02:07:56.000 --> 02:08:00.000
I think it went running against Julian Bond when we went down.

02:08:00.000 --> 02:08:02.000
I think we went the first time.

02:08:02.000 --> 02:08:05.000
And he went running against Julian Bond at that time,

02:08:05.000 --> 02:08:10.000
because (Marion) Barry and all of us got to modicate together

02:08:10.000 --> 02:08:15.000
and went to help him out.

02:08:15.000 --> 02:08:16.000
Yeah, I'm not sure.

02:08:16.000 --> 02:08:17.000
Now, I don't think it was,

02:08:17.000 --> 02:08:19.000
because we wouldn't have went if he was against Julian Bond.

02:08:19.000 --> 02:08:23.000
So he was the problem of the first time.

02:08:23.000 --> 02:08:27.000
One of the reasons I asked is,

02:08:27.000 --> 02:08:29.000
well, I'm jumping ahead a little bit,

02:08:29.000 --> 02:08:32.000
but what kind of,

02:08:32.000 --> 02:08:34.000
as people left next,

02:08:34.000 --> 02:08:37.000
there's been a lot of different kinds of settings,

02:08:37.000 --> 02:08:39.000
many ways, things like the continuous,

02:08:39.000 --> 02:08:41.000
so there's really as an example,

02:08:41.000 --> 02:08:45.000
got involved with drum and steel books for,

02:08:45.000 --> 02:08:47.000
a lot of people,

02:08:47.000 --> 02:08:51.000
working in Lowndes County.

02:08:51.000 --> 02:08:55.000
When the Bobbys, Lowndes County,

02:08:55.000 --> 02:08:57.000
because when they were,

02:08:57.000 --> 02:08:59.000
he was in that first group,

02:08:59.000 --> 02:09:00.000
so when they moved back.

02:09:00.000 --> 02:09:03.000
He was, he was, he was, he was.

02:09:03.000 --> 02:09:07.000
So what did you do when you came out of tune?

02:09:07.000 --> 02:09:16.000
I left, I left SNCC in 60,

02:09:16.000 --> 02:09:20.000
65, D765.

02:09:20.000 --> 02:09:22.000
Meg Due was here in DC,

02:09:22.000 --> 02:09:28.000
and he was director of the United Planning Organization,

02:09:28.000 --> 02:09:32.000
center number one,

02:09:32.000 --> 02:09:38.000
and he brought me on as his second-in-command in the center.

02:09:38.000 --> 02:09:41.000
We ran that center for about a year,

02:09:41.000 --> 02:09:45.000
before politically, we got put out,

02:09:45.000 --> 02:09:49.000
then after that,

02:09:49.000 --> 02:09:53.000
Ed Brown,

02:09:53.000 --> 02:09:55.000
Ed Brown.

02:09:55.000 --> 02:09:58.000
Ed Brown asked me to come back to Atlanta,

02:09:58.000 --> 02:10:00.000
come back to Mississippi,

02:10:00.000 --> 02:10:05.000
and work for the Child Development Group of Mississippi.

02:10:05.000 --> 02:10:12.000
I went in as the Social Service Director.

02:10:12.000 --> 02:10:16.000
I worked there as the Social Service Director

02:10:16.000 --> 02:10:20.000
until I got put out of there.

02:10:20.000 --> 02:10:22.000
Because I was out of,

02:10:22.000 --> 02:10:25.000
well they were in the process of breaking up Child Development Group of Mississippi,

02:10:25.000 --> 02:10:27.000
and we were at this meeting with,

02:10:27.000 --> 02:10:30.000
with, with one of Stenesis,

02:10:30.000 --> 02:10:33.000
Senator John C. Stennis,

02:10:33.000 --> 02:10:36.000
and this man just kept,

02:10:36.000 --> 02:10:38.000
every time he got ready to say something,

02:10:38.000 --> 02:10:41.000
he would, he would preface it with,

02:10:41.000 --> 02:10:44.000
can I say something, you boys?

02:10:44.000 --> 02:10:47.000
You boys,

02:10:47.000 --> 02:10:49.000
and can I tell you boys,

02:10:49.000 --> 02:10:52.000
so finally I just,

02:10:52.000 --> 02:10:53.000
I asked him,

02:10:53.000 --> 02:10:55.000
I asked you a question.

02:10:55.000 --> 02:10:57.000
That's why,

02:10:57.000 --> 02:11:00.000
is it that every time you get ready to say something to us,

02:11:00.000 --> 02:11:03.000
you've got to put some preference on about you boys,

02:11:03.000 --> 02:11:06.000
and a damn boy in this room.

02:11:06.000 --> 02:11:08.000
Well,

02:11:08.000 --> 02:11:10.000
you know what happened after that.

02:11:11.000 --> 02:11:13.000
I had lost my job

02:11:13.000 --> 02:11:15.000
because you don't talk to Stenesis.

02:11:15.000 --> 02:11:17.000
You don't talk to white men in Mississippi that way,

02:11:17.000 --> 02:11:21.000
and you don't talk to Senator John C. Stennis that way.

02:11:21.000 --> 02:11:25.000
So I got fired again.

02:11:25.000 --> 02:11:28.000
So then,

02:11:28.000 --> 02:11:31.000
no day

02:11:31.000 --> 02:11:36.000
who was married to Peggy Dammond

02:11:36.000 --> 02:11:39.000
was part of an organization called,

02:11:39.000 --> 02:11:42.000
OSTI,

02:11:42.000 --> 02:11:49.000
the OSTI.

02:11:49.000 --> 02:11:52.000
There was,

02:11:52.000 --> 02:11:56.000
and they were foolish yet to.

02:11:56.000 --> 02:12:00.000
No brought me in

02:12:00.000 --> 02:12:05.000
because they were dealing with a lot of housing situations,

02:12:05.000 --> 02:12:08.000
and they were dealing with a lot of community people,

02:12:08.000 --> 02:12:11.000
and involved in,

02:12:11.000 --> 02:12:14.000
well, the first project was Detroit,

02:12:14.000 --> 02:12:17.000
and we were working with a free Detroit committee,

02:12:17.000 --> 02:12:19.000
and Detroit was getting me,

02:12:19.000 --> 02:12:22.000
the free Detroit committee was getting me a takeover east side,

02:12:22.000 --> 02:12:26.000
and there was this community lady that was blocking them

02:12:26.000 --> 02:12:28.000
from doing it,

02:12:28.000 --> 02:12:30.000
and they didn't have nobody.

02:12:30.000 --> 02:12:32.000
They was going up and they're talking to this lady,

02:12:32.000 --> 02:12:34.000
knowing what she was going on.

02:12:34.000 --> 02:12:36.000
So that was the first time.

02:12:36.000 --> 02:12:42.000
So they were going to be caught up into going into the black community

02:12:42.000 --> 02:12:45.000
and reporting back.

02:12:45.000 --> 02:12:50.000
Well, after that project,

02:12:50.000 --> 02:12:52.000
I went on a,

02:12:52.000 --> 02:12:55.000
no-oil had talked to

02:12:55.000 --> 02:12:57.000
Kaiser Engineers,

02:12:57.000 --> 02:13:00.000
out of Oakland, California.

02:13:00.000 --> 02:13:05.000
He had convinced Kaiser Engineers

02:13:05.000 --> 02:13:08.000
to work with the Panthers

02:13:08.000 --> 02:13:14.000
to acquisition a piece of land

02:13:14.000 --> 02:13:20.000
called correct in East Oakland.

02:13:20.000 --> 02:13:24.000
They were going to,

02:13:24.000 --> 02:13:29.000
from acquisition to building,

02:13:30.000 --> 02:13:36.000
planning, acquisition, planning, building, managing all of this,

02:13:36.000 --> 02:13:39.000
and it was based on a 40-year plan,

02:13:39.000 --> 02:13:43.000
but it didn't have nobody to get to the Panthers.

02:13:43.000 --> 02:13:47.000
So no-oil had me to come out,

02:13:47.000 --> 02:13:50.000
and of course,

02:13:50.000 --> 02:13:52.000
find a way into the Panthers.

02:13:52.000 --> 02:13:55.000
Of course, I knew Stokely in,

02:13:55.000 --> 02:13:58.000
I knew Stokely was going to be a rap in everybody.

02:13:58.000 --> 02:14:01.000
So I started talking to him and they said,

02:14:01.000 --> 02:14:04.000
yeah, we might be used this one.

02:14:04.000 --> 02:14:07.000
We'll go for this one.

02:14:07.000 --> 02:14:11.000
So then he turned me over to the Oakland people.

02:14:11.000 --> 02:14:15.000
Well, when I went to the meeting,

02:14:15.000 --> 02:14:19.000
I was in Oakland maybe for a couple of weeks or so.

02:14:19.000 --> 02:14:24.000
And when I went to the meeting with the Panthers,

02:14:24.000 --> 02:14:28.000
I was told, we're not going to deal with you.

02:14:28.000 --> 02:14:30.000
One because you've been right around town

02:14:30.000 --> 02:14:33.000
and a steel-grade Cadillac.

02:14:33.000 --> 02:14:36.000
I said, well, that belongs to Kaiser Cement,

02:14:36.000 --> 02:14:38.000
and well, you belong to them.

02:14:38.000 --> 02:14:42.000
And I said, would you haven't even heard what I got to offer?

02:14:42.000 --> 02:14:44.000
Well, we've heard a little bit of it.

02:14:44.000 --> 02:14:46.000
I mean, we don't believe it.

02:14:46.000 --> 02:14:48.000
I said, thank you.

02:14:48.000 --> 02:14:51.000
I called Noel and I said, hey, you ain't no deal.

02:14:51.000 --> 02:14:55.000
You don't need to go through this bullshit.

02:14:55.000 --> 02:15:00.000
So in the meantime, I met other people in town.

02:15:00.000 --> 02:15:03.000
So I said, well, no, there may be a way out of this.

02:15:03.000 --> 02:15:05.000
I've met some community folk.

02:15:05.000 --> 02:15:09.000
Maybe we can switch it over and give it to the community folk.

02:15:09.000 --> 02:15:13.000
So he said, well, see what you can do.

02:15:13.000 --> 02:15:17.000
Timothy L. Jenkins,

02:15:18.000 --> 02:15:24.000
who was an advisor to SNCC from the very beginning

02:15:24.000 --> 02:15:26.000
and Tim comes out of Yale,

02:15:26.000 --> 02:15:33.000
out of National Student Association.

02:15:33.000 --> 02:15:42.000
Tim is always, I consider it to be the mouthpiece of SNCC.

02:15:42.000 --> 02:15:46.000
So I called him mouthpiece and I said,

02:15:46.000 --> 02:15:50.000
hey, man, didn't you introduce me to somebody

02:15:50.000 --> 02:15:52.000
that you had a partner somewhere out here?

02:15:52.000 --> 02:15:54.000
I'm out here in Oakland, California.

02:15:54.000 --> 02:15:59.000
And he said, yeah, I got a man out there by the name of Don Warden.

02:15:59.000 --> 02:16:04.000
I said, okay, then I told Tim what I was doing and he said, okay.

02:16:04.000 --> 02:16:06.000
Look him up.

02:16:06.000 --> 02:16:10.000
So I looked up Don Warden.

02:16:10.000 --> 02:16:14.000
I got with Don Warden and then I met him as his love

02:16:14.000 --> 02:16:19.000
who was in charge of Social Service Department of Oakland.

02:16:19.000 --> 02:16:25.000
I met Mr. Dumbro who was a construction person.

02:16:25.000 --> 02:16:32.000
I'm thinking the NAACP's person name was Wes.

02:16:32.000 --> 02:16:33.000
I'm not sure about that.

02:16:33.000 --> 02:16:38.000
But I formed a community group.

02:16:38.000 --> 02:16:43.000
That community group got together with Kaiser.

02:16:43.000 --> 02:16:47.000
Got the acquisition of the land.

02:16:47.000 --> 02:16:54.000
The senior citizens I was sitting today called West Project Equal.

02:16:54.000 --> 02:17:03.000
What was the title of motivation?

02:17:03.000 --> 02:17:09.000
I think Lord will tell me that the Kaiser was trying to show

02:17:09.000 --> 02:17:16.000
some level of calmness that could happen.

02:17:16.000 --> 02:17:21.000
There would be a demonstration that other things could happen.

02:17:21.000 --> 02:17:25.000
If housing was a problem, this is one way that you could do it.

02:17:25.000 --> 02:17:31.000
And it was a way to show folks who had not been involved in acquisitions

02:17:31.000 --> 02:17:36.000
and all of the processes of going about building houses

02:17:36.000 --> 02:17:41.000
or getting into the business, they were willing to put up the money.

02:17:41.000 --> 02:17:45.000
And this was from big Kaiser aluminum.

02:17:45.000 --> 02:17:52.000
This was a subsidiary of Kaiser aluminum sitting there in Oakland.

02:17:52.000 --> 02:17:56.000
And I guess this was part of their payback to Oakland.

02:17:56.000 --> 02:18:01.000
So I stayed with this company for a little while longer.

02:18:01.000 --> 02:18:05.000
They had several construction contracts with different cities

02:18:05.000 --> 02:18:09.000
with the model cities kind of stuff.

02:18:09.000 --> 02:18:13.000
And each time I would be called in to go talk to the black community

02:18:13.000 --> 02:18:18.000
but I couldn't hear what was going on in the white community.

02:18:18.000 --> 02:18:22.000
So finally in a meeting I said,

02:18:22.000 --> 02:18:34.000
Why do I have to say, why can't I know what's going on in the white folks meeting?

02:18:34.000 --> 02:18:39.000
When I only got to go to the black folks meeting and take back what y'all see

02:18:39.000 --> 02:18:44.000
happened in the white folks meeting. Why ain't I there to understand what's going on?

02:18:44.000 --> 02:18:51.000
Well, you don't need to understand what's going on and you fight.

02:18:51.000 --> 02:18:54.000
Yeah, I'm really telling you.

02:18:54.000 --> 02:18:58.000
So I'm out on the street again.

02:18:58.000 --> 02:19:01.000
I'm married by this time.

02:19:01.000 --> 02:19:10.000
I got married late 66, 67 so when I got last at four years.

02:19:10.000 --> 02:19:17.000
I'm now having back pains.

02:19:17.000 --> 02:19:24.000
I'm having real sharp, sharp back pains.

02:19:24.000 --> 02:19:33.000
So I go to the doctor and the doctor tells me I'm having muscle spasms.

02:19:33.000 --> 02:19:38.000
And he gives me these little yellow pills and he tells me I have to take,

02:19:38.000 --> 02:19:46.000
take them three times a day and after I take them I have to sleep for two hours.

02:19:47.000 --> 02:19:55.000
I left the doctor's office and stopped by my favorite drugist.

02:19:55.000 --> 02:20:01.000
And back then in the days you could get a whole sharp back full of riefer for $10.

02:20:01.000 --> 02:20:07.000
I got me some riefer and I went and got me a fifth of Jack Daniels.

02:20:07.000 --> 02:20:13.000
I went home in that same chair that I have sitting in my bedroom now.

02:20:14.000 --> 02:20:20.000
I sat in my chair, I sat the pills on my desk.

02:20:20.000 --> 02:20:25.000
And I took me a shot of Jack Daniels, I rolled me a joint.

02:20:25.000 --> 02:20:31.000
And I sat there and I was trying to figure out how I'm going to sleep for six hours.

02:20:31.000 --> 02:20:33.000
Take care of family.

02:20:33.000 --> 02:20:38.000
Well, I only had the wife at the time but how am I going to work and sleep six hours?

02:20:38.000 --> 02:20:42.000
Well, the first conclusion I came to, that couldn't be done.

02:20:43.000 --> 02:20:49.000
So then I started thinking about all of the things that was happening to me at the time.

02:20:49.000 --> 02:20:58.000
I had just been out on a consultancy with a buddy and I was working what we called a fish tank.

02:20:58.000 --> 02:21:05.000
We were working for this black consultant, this black architect that had a black and white staff

02:21:05.000 --> 02:21:08.000
and he went to sensitize the staff.

02:21:09.000 --> 02:21:14.000
So I had all of these people in the room that I knew something more than each one of them.

02:21:14.000 --> 02:21:23.000
And I had to make them interact in order to get them to understand that this man wanted you to do his work

02:21:23.000 --> 02:21:27.000
and to hell with whatever you might think of him and whatever you might think of him.

02:21:27.000 --> 02:21:29.000
Just get the contracts done.

02:21:29.000 --> 02:21:34.000
Well, afterwards my boys, my guys with Thomas and Reggie did a great job

02:21:34.000 --> 02:21:41.000
but you almost blew the act because you smoked three packs of cigarettes in an hour.

02:21:41.000 --> 02:21:48.000
So that thought kind of came to me and I lit up another joint.

02:21:48.000 --> 02:21:55.000
And I said to myself, maybe cigarettes has got something to do with it.

02:21:55.000 --> 02:21:59.000
So I decided the next day I was not going to smoke.

02:21:59.000 --> 02:22:02.000
I was going to do everything I did.

02:22:02.000 --> 02:22:05.000
Normally every day and I did went through the day.

02:22:05.000 --> 02:22:10.000
I came home but wife was blowing smoke because she smoked at the time.

02:22:10.000 --> 02:22:16.000
She was blowing smoke on my face and it's, so I talked to a buddy the second day.

02:22:16.000 --> 02:22:20.000
And he told me, say you go three days baby, you got it made.

02:22:20.000 --> 02:22:23.000
I went fishing the third day.

02:22:23.000 --> 02:22:26.000
I ain't smoked since.

02:22:26.000 --> 02:22:30.000
I was up to three to nothing.

02:22:30.000 --> 02:22:34.000
I just stopped.

02:22:34.000 --> 02:22:37.000
I continued to look at the next few days.

02:22:37.000 --> 02:22:41.000
I continued to look at them pills and say they ain't over yet.

02:22:41.000 --> 02:22:45.000
Then I thought about coffee.

02:22:45.000 --> 02:22:48.000
I'd get out to be and put my feet on the floor.

02:22:48.000 --> 02:22:50.000
I had to get a cup of coffee.

02:22:50.000 --> 02:22:52.000
I could floor I could wash my teeth.

02:22:52.000 --> 02:22:54.000
I could get a cup of coffee.

02:22:54.000 --> 02:22:57.000
Before I sit down and have a cup of coffee, I had to have a cup of coffee.

02:22:57.000 --> 02:23:00.000
I go to, I take the bus.

02:23:00.000 --> 02:23:03.000
Before I could get on the bus, I'd have a cup of coffee.

02:23:03.000 --> 02:23:06.000
Get off the bus, get on the train, have another cup of coffee.

02:23:06.000 --> 02:23:12.000
Before I walk into office, have a cup of coffee, get to the office, have a cup of phone ring, got to have a cup of coffee.

02:23:12.000 --> 02:23:14.000
Interview somebody, got to have a cup of coffee.

02:23:14.000 --> 02:23:17.000
I'm like this here.

02:23:17.000 --> 02:23:20.000
So I said, well.

02:23:20.000 --> 02:23:23.000
Coffee is the other one.

02:23:23.000 --> 02:23:28.000
So I got rid of coffee and started drinking tea and other kinds of things.

02:23:28.000 --> 02:23:31.000
Feeling a little better now.

02:23:31.000 --> 02:23:36.000
Now I'm working, but I'm working at something I do not like.

02:23:36.000 --> 02:23:40.000
I do not like because I'm not free.

02:23:40.000 --> 02:23:44.000
I'm caught up into taking care of family.

02:23:44.000 --> 02:23:51.000
My daddy's always, my daddy taught me, my daddy got paid the whole family sat there and he dealt with the money.

02:23:51.000 --> 02:23:54.000
He took care of family first.

02:23:54.000 --> 02:23:57.000
Then he looked at his hand and said, work shoes.

02:23:57.000 --> 02:24:01.000
And then whatever else he had to do, that's the way I felt.

02:24:01.000 --> 02:24:05.000
I was in a position that, in that first, OSTI thing.

02:24:05.000 --> 02:24:08.000
I didn't even see my paycheck.

02:24:08.000 --> 02:24:11.000
I went to the bank.

02:24:11.000 --> 02:24:14.000
She had the bank account.

02:24:14.000 --> 02:24:17.000
I was one of the expensive accounts.

02:24:17.000 --> 02:24:21.000
I had no expense account to do anything I wanted to do.

02:24:21.000 --> 02:24:25.000
So I didn't even see money.

02:24:25.000 --> 02:24:29.000
Now there's little other little jobs that I'm doing there.

02:24:29.000 --> 02:24:32.000
I see the money.

02:24:32.000 --> 02:24:36.000
I mean, I'm doing shit that I just do not like.

02:24:36.000 --> 02:24:39.000
So the job is a problem.

02:24:39.000 --> 02:24:49.000
Well, the job of becoming a problem, the marriage is becoming a problem for all kinds of reasons.

02:24:49.000 --> 02:24:56.000
So Bobby Yancy calls me.

02:24:56.000 --> 02:25:03.000
Oh, I finally got, well, I hadn't gotten quite got rid of the other job yet, but I'm on my way.

02:25:03.000 --> 02:25:10.000
I had rid of this job because this job is part of my misery.

02:25:10.000 --> 02:25:12.000
No, no, no, no, no, no.

02:25:12.000 --> 02:25:15.000
That was just a quick consultancy.

02:25:15.000 --> 02:25:19.000
No, no, no, that was an outside job.

02:25:19.000 --> 02:25:22.000
Now I've left Austin.

02:25:22.000 --> 02:25:28.000
I'm working for, who am I working for?

02:25:28.000 --> 02:25:31.000
I'm a Western University.

02:25:31.000 --> 02:25:40.000
I'm doing one of them welfare programs where they got to teach people to read and write or else they get put off a welfare.

02:25:40.000 --> 02:25:51.000
I got a school more or less that's running from kindergarten to high school with 35 year old women.

02:25:51.000 --> 02:26:00.000
And derelict men and, oh, Lord, have mercy.

02:26:00.000 --> 02:26:14.000
And young students who haven't got their life together and crashing out and it's just becoming, you know, I'm just not wanting all of this stuff.

02:26:14.000 --> 02:26:21.000
I've been married to a psychiatric social worker too and I'm just used to doing my own hustle.

02:26:21.000 --> 02:26:32.000
And one of the things that me and my wife had agreement on is that once she got her masters, then she would handle things as we'd talk about little babies until things get right.

02:26:32.000 --> 02:26:35.000
Then you take care of things while I put mine together.

02:26:35.000 --> 02:26:40.000
Well, of course, by the time it came round for me, go to school, do this.

02:26:40.000 --> 02:26:45.000
Well, I didn't tell you what to do.

02:26:45.000 --> 02:26:51.000
Do what you do and I'll do what I'll do and I'll guarantee you everything will work out well.

02:26:51.000 --> 02:26:53.000
All of that's happening.

02:26:54.000 --> 02:26:59.000
I'm getting this phone call from Bobby Nancy.

02:26:59.000 --> 02:27:05.000
Bobby says, got a project in Memphis, Tennessee.

02:27:05.000 --> 02:27:11.000
If you're free, come right away.

02:27:12.000 --> 02:27:16.000
I had a dog. I made it home.

02:27:16.000 --> 02:27:21.000
I walked through the door and there she was, my ex-wife.

02:27:21.000 --> 02:27:28.000
And she says, I'm getting another apartment.

02:27:28.000 --> 02:27:30.000
I'm leaving.

02:27:30.000 --> 02:27:39.000
And what I said to her when we first met was, whenever you get tired of me and you don't hesitate to tell me that you're going to go.

02:27:39.000 --> 02:27:42.000
That's the end, that's the end.

02:27:42.000 --> 02:27:47.000
So when she said it, I said, no, hold still.

02:27:47.000 --> 02:27:52.000
I said, I'm going away for maybe about six weeks.

02:27:52.000 --> 02:27:56.000
And when I get back, then we talk or something or other.

02:27:56.000 --> 02:28:01.000
And I, over the course of time, I already packed some bags and stuff.

02:28:01.000 --> 02:28:05.000
So I went on to this project.

02:28:05.000 --> 02:28:22.000
The project was one of the first black caucus dinners in Memphis, Tennessee working for A.L. A.L. Nellum & Associates & Associates.

02:28:22.000 --> 02:28:34.000
So we did that project and we came on back and Bobby gave me the option to meet her in DC because she was getting ready to take over a whole project here.

02:28:34.000 --> 02:28:42.000
So I came back to Boston and things ain't what they used to be and ain't what they were.

02:28:42.000 --> 02:28:52.000
I said, all of that stuff I got packed in the corner in my records and my chair.

02:28:52.000 --> 02:28:58.000
And my chair, sitting at the address, I'll send you in.

02:28:58.000 --> 02:29:05.000
I left Boston and I've been back here in DC since 81.

02:29:05.000 --> 02:29:12.000
What's some of you think so many people have come to DC but maybe they're home?

02:29:12.000 --> 02:29:18.000
Well, you can make a living here.

02:29:18.000 --> 02:29:27.000
And then with so many of us here, we could get together and help each other.

02:29:27.000 --> 02:29:47.000
One of the things that happened to me, even after I, after Bobby took the position with A.L. Nellum & Associates, it wasn't a solid kind of thing to do because he wasn't prepared to do the kinds of operations that was necessary to do the kinds of fundraising that was necessary.

02:29:47.000 --> 02:30:10.000
So the project just kind of fell apart and then there I was out there again but because of who I knew around town, I could get other consultancies and little things to survive and then friends would loan me money to pay rent if I couldn't find the rent.

02:30:10.000 --> 02:30:20.000
And then I got involved in the charter along with John A. Wilson.

02:30:20.000 --> 02:30:38.000
I met and made friends that way and I was involved with a computer company called Afro-American Data Namix,

02:30:38.000 --> 02:30:56.000
which was at 14th and Kenyon and it had the only computer on the ground outside of any black institution between here in New York and it was a DEC PDP-11/45.

02:30:56.000 --> 02:31:01.000
It recovered its room.

02:31:01.000 --> 02:31:09.000
And I was hooked up with a... got it right here.

02:31:09.000 --> 02:31:18.000
So we did all kinds of activities such as what our main thing was doing polls and things.

02:31:18.000 --> 02:31:29.000
And we did ((Marion) Barry) Barry, very first poll to the numbers and showed where he hooked everybody.

02:31:29.000 --> 02:31:45.000
And of course showing him that and working things out after the election we were rewarded with a few contracts and things were going very well.

02:31:45.000 --> 02:31:52.000
But back then, his days, electricity was bigger than what we could do.

02:31:52.000 --> 02:32:01.000
We couldn't keep that big machine rolling and couldn't bring it enough contracts to keep it rolling so the lights went out.

02:32:01.000 --> 02:32:12.000
So after that, I kind of went on unemployment for a few years, which was a good thing.

02:32:12.000 --> 02:32:23.000
Then I was asked to come in and work with the youth division at what I worked for Pride before then.

02:32:23.000 --> 02:32:29.000
But I was asked to come in and work with the youth division and the Department of Employment Services.

02:32:29.000 --> 02:32:40.000
When (Marion) Barry was doing his first... well, it was the time he was doing his second summer youth program.

02:32:40.000 --> 02:32:43.000
When we did the 40,000.

02:32:43.000 --> 02:32:49.000
The first time was kind of a disaster because they hadn't done the checks and balances.

02:32:49.000 --> 02:32:54.000
It was necessary to keep up and match up these kids.

02:32:54.000 --> 02:33:01.000
So we matched up kids and kids went to the right places. They got their checks and it was a successful program.

02:33:01.000 --> 02:33:10.000
And we did 40,000 one year in the summer and 25,000 in the school year.

02:33:10.000 --> 02:33:15.000
I stayed with that program for about two, three years.

02:33:15.000 --> 02:33:29.000
Then I went to work as an investigator for the Department of Employment Services in the Department of Employment, unemployment insurance.

02:33:29.000 --> 02:33:36.000
And I busted quite a few.

02:33:36.000 --> 02:33:46.000
And I sorted quite a few who was arrested.

02:33:46.000 --> 02:33:52.000
And at that time the government was changing over from paper to data.

02:33:52.000 --> 02:33:55.000
And I got involved in that.

02:33:55.000 --> 02:34:02.000
And when I left the government, I was an assistant land administrator.

02:34:02.000 --> 02:34:13.000
I was operating at least 100 machines managing and making that 100 machines.

02:34:13.000 --> 02:34:24.000
I left the government 20 years to the day.

02:34:24.000 --> 02:34:30.000
Only because I had planned to stay longer to help my partner.

02:34:30.000 --> 02:34:38.000
Because I promised her I would help her until she got through to got all of the data in and straight.

02:34:38.000 --> 02:34:41.000
And she was moving pretty well.

02:34:41.000 --> 02:34:45.000
And I promised to stay with her until October.

02:34:45.000 --> 02:34:49.000
But that may.

02:34:49.000 --> 02:34:53.000
We were very, very busy one day.

02:34:53.000 --> 02:34:58.000
I mean, we had elbow, I mean, elbow elbows and work.

02:34:58.000 --> 02:35:05.000
And the director came up and said, all right, everybody stop and go down to the war memorial.

02:35:05.000 --> 02:35:09.000
So we said, well, why would we have to do that?

02:35:09.000 --> 02:35:11.000
I mean, we're busy in that way.

02:35:11.000 --> 02:35:13.000
Well, everybody has to be there.

02:35:13.000 --> 02:35:19.000
So we went, of course, bosses tell you what to do.

02:35:19.000 --> 02:35:20.000
Yes.

02:35:20.000 --> 02:35:25.000
So we get down to the memorial and we hear this person.

02:35:25.000 --> 02:35:28.000
So this person finishes what he's got to say.

02:35:28.000 --> 02:35:36.000
And then he says, I'm like, and as you leave, I'll pick up my records and tapes.

02:35:36.000 --> 02:35:40.000
So I turn to my partner and I said, did I hear him, right?

02:35:40.000 --> 02:35:42.000
Pick up records and tape.

02:35:42.000 --> 02:35:44.000
What is this we're doing?

02:35:44.000 --> 02:35:52.000
And then I find out that this guy was somebody they hired to come in as an incentive speaker

02:35:52.000 --> 02:35:55.000
to get us to do more work.

02:35:55.000 --> 02:35:58.000
And here we were in elbows, ass hole, beeping work.

02:35:58.000 --> 02:36:01.000
And they take us, I said, no, this don't make no sense.

02:36:01.000 --> 02:36:05.000
So I said, Linda, I see you back up town.

02:36:05.000 --> 02:36:06.000
She said, where are you going?

02:36:06.000 --> 02:36:08.000
I said, I'm going to person now.

02:36:08.000 --> 02:36:13.000
I said, this is kind of bullshit that's coming down and down through this administration.

02:36:13.000 --> 02:36:14.000
It just come in.

02:36:14.000 --> 02:36:16.000
The new administration just come in.

02:36:16.000 --> 02:36:19.000
And they got new people coming in with all of this.

02:36:20.000 --> 02:36:22.000
I said, this is the kind of bullshit that's coming in.

02:36:22.000 --> 02:36:25.000
I'm going.

02:36:25.000 --> 02:36:27.000
I went down, put in my papers.

02:36:27.000 --> 02:36:30.000
I was 62 years old.

02:36:30.000 --> 02:36:32.000
I was at May.

02:36:32.000 --> 02:36:34.000
And I came in in May 61.

02:36:34.000 --> 02:36:37.000
And I left May 2001.

02:36:37.000 --> 02:36:45.000
I've been out now 15 years doing exactly what I started out to do.

02:36:46.000 --> 02:36:52.000
In 1961, it's become a free black person.

02:36:52.000 --> 02:37:02.000
And if you notice my emails, I come on my last name, the red comma, FBP.

02:37:02.000 --> 02:37:04.000
And I'm dead serious about it.

02:37:04.000 --> 02:37:07.000
I am a free black person.

02:37:07.000 --> 02:37:13.000
I do every and any thing I want to do.

02:37:13.000 --> 02:37:16.000
And that was the purpose of starting out.

02:37:16.000 --> 02:37:17.000
That was the goal.

02:37:17.000 --> 02:37:21.000
That was my goal to become independent.

02:37:21.000 --> 02:37:23.000
I ain't got no money.

02:37:23.000 --> 02:37:24.000
But you're independent.

02:37:24.000 --> 02:37:27.000
If I'm independent, then I'm rich.

02:37:39.000 --> 02:37:42.000
Hey, dude, what you got to do?

02:37:42.000 --> 02:37:45.000
I took you long enough to get this one.

02:37:45.000 --> 02:37:48.000
So you were...

02:37:51.000 --> 02:37:54.000
I know, and I ain't got money.

02:38:03.000 --> 02:38:06.000
What were you doing in summer?

02:38:06.000 --> 02:38:09.000
64.

02:38:09.000 --> 02:38:13.000
64.

02:38:13.000 --> 02:38:17.000
64.

02:38:17.000 --> 02:38:19.000
64.

02:38:19.000 --> 02:38:23.000
64.

02:38:23.000 --> 02:38:25.000
Oh, I was in New York.

02:38:25.000 --> 02:38:27.000
I was fundraising.

02:38:27.000 --> 02:38:28.000
I was fundraising.

02:38:28.000 --> 02:38:29.000
Yeah, I was fundraising.

02:38:29.000 --> 02:38:34.000
Well, actually, all through 64, after the...

02:38:34.000 --> 02:38:35.000
I see.

02:38:35.000 --> 02:38:38.000
I left...

02:38:38.000 --> 02:38:43.000
I left and went to work for Senator Joseph D. Tydings,

02:38:43.000 --> 02:38:49.000
Senator Joseph D. Tydings, just before the challenge.

02:38:49.000 --> 02:38:51.000
I spoke with Ms. Baker about it,

02:38:51.000 --> 02:38:55.000
and she says, well, if you feel as though he's going to advance you

02:38:55.000 --> 02:38:58.000
in understanding what's going on and everything,

02:38:58.000 --> 02:39:01.000
then go ahead and do it.

02:39:01.000 --> 02:39:03.000
So I did that.

02:39:03.000 --> 02:39:05.000
Then I came back.

02:39:05.000 --> 02:39:12.000
Then I was assigned to go and lobby for the MFDP.

02:39:12.000 --> 02:39:20.000
I went to California, and I went to Oregon.

02:39:20.000 --> 02:39:26.000
I came back, and then I was sent down to Atlantic City

02:39:26.000 --> 02:39:33.000
to assist in locating housing and necessary stuff.

02:39:33.000 --> 02:39:38.000
Support pieces for the people coming in.

02:39:38.000 --> 02:39:45.000
Hooked up with Mary Lovelace O'Neal, who was from NAG,

02:39:45.000 --> 02:39:50.000
who was already on the job, trying to deal with this thing,

02:39:50.000 --> 02:39:58.000
and Mary being one of those beautiful, beautiful black gals

02:39:58.000 --> 02:40:04.000
of our outfit, we ran into one of the biggest gangsters

02:40:04.000 --> 02:40:09.000
in Atlantic City by the name of Reggie Edgel,

02:40:09.000 --> 02:40:13.000
and all of a sudden, we started getting hotel rooms

02:40:13.000 --> 02:40:16.000
and accommodations, and everything else

02:40:16.000 --> 02:40:21.000
that was necessary for us to bring out people in.

02:40:21.000 --> 02:40:26.000
Then after that, then I was sent to New York

02:40:26.000 --> 02:40:30.000
to do special gift fundraising.

02:40:30.000 --> 02:40:35.000
I stayed in New York until I went to...

02:40:35.000 --> 02:40:39.000
That's when I was doing special gift stuff.

02:40:39.000 --> 02:40:43.000
Then from there, I was assigned to go to Philadelphia

02:40:43.000 --> 02:40:50.000
office for fundraising.

02:40:50.000 --> 02:40:55.000
Then a person by the name of Fred Mealy came to town,

02:40:55.000 --> 02:41:01.000
and just... I guess I can say, fucked up.

02:41:01.000 --> 02:41:05.000
Everything that we had built, and was going

02:41:05.000 --> 02:41:09.000
in an opposite direction, and we lost our gains

02:41:09.000 --> 02:41:11.000
that we had in Philly.

02:41:11.000 --> 02:41:15.000
Then Jim pulled me out of Philly, and was sending me

02:41:15.000 --> 02:41:20.000
to Texas to meet up with a group of people

02:41:20.000 --> 02:41:24.000
who wanted to do some fundraising in Texas.

02:41:24.000 --> 02:41:28.000
Now I've got to go through Atlanta,

02:41:28.000 --> 02:41:33.000
and this is about late 65 now,

02:41:33.000 --> 02:41:36.000
and things are in a disarray.

02:41:36.000 --> 02:41:40.000
They don't know which way to go and what to do and what to do.

02:41:40.000 --> 02:41:47.000
So by the end of the year, MacDoo calls me, and I leave.

02:41:47.000 --> 02:41:52.000
So I wasn't... That's what I was doing at 64.

02:41:52.000 --> 02:41:55.000
So, things like you were...

02:41:55.000 --> 02:41:58.000
Like you did everything, or things like you were the first thing

02:41:58.000 --> 02:42:02.000
that we call the call, so that everybody was leaving.

02:42:02.000 --> 02:42:04.000
Or like, is that...

02:42:04.000 --> 02:42:09.000
Call me that, or call me a Vance man, call me the Pickup man.

02:42:10.000 --> 02:42:13.000
I'll make you just allow me.

02:42:13.000 --> 02:42:20.000
Yeah, because one time, we weren't getting reports out of the field.

02:42:20.000 --> 02:42:24.000
So Jim and I jumped in the car, and of course I don't drive.

02:42:24.000 --> 02:42:28.000
And we drove to all of our projects through Mississippi,

02:42:28.000 --> 02:42:33.000
through Georgia, Alabama, and everywhere.

02:42:33.000 --> 02:42:36.000
I even went up to check on the...

02:42:36.000 --> 02:42:41.000
DeGens of Defense in North Carolina.

02:42:41.000 --> 02:42:47.000
And while Jim did that, I talked to people and got reports

02:42:47.000 --> 02:42:53.000
and put reports back to Julian Bond, even written reports and phone calls and stuff like that.

02:42:53.000 --> 02:42:56.000
Is it probably 65?

02:42:56.000 --> 02:42:57.000
Is it 65?

02:42:57.000 --> 02:43:00.000
This is...

02:43:00.000 --> 02:43:03.000
This is 63.

02:43:03.000 --> 02:43:05.000
Is it 63?

02:43:05.000 --> 02:43:09.000
64.

02:43:09.000 --> 02:43:13.000
I don't start the light activity until...

02:43:13.000 --> 02:43:18.000
Until after 60, until about 60, late 64.

02:43:18.000 --> 02:43:25.000
You tried Jim for them, and so people you had didn't have a chance to meet me.

02:43:25.000 --> 02:43:29.000
I would have described the boss.

02:43:31.000 --> 02:43:36.000
Well, he was a matter of fact kind of guy.

02:43:36.000 --> 02:43:41.000
He was a military thinking kind of person.

02:43:41.000 --> 02:43:46.000
He was a person that could tell you the plan,

02:43:46.000 --> 02:43:48.000
and almost...

02:43:48.000 --> 02:43:51.000
And tell you your spot in the plan.

02:43:51.000 --> 02:43:56.000
And if you carried out your spot and bring it back, it fit.

02:43:57.000 --> 02:44:03.000
If you deviated from the plan too much, it didn't fit.

02:44:03.000 --> 02:44:11.000
But if you followed him, and it did it the way he wanted it to do,

02:44:11.000 --> 02:44:14.000
everything would work out.

02:44:14.000 --> 02:44:18.000
Were you in the meetings, all of the big meetings about what you did,

02:44:18.000 --> 02:44:21.000
what kind of structures should have,

02:44:21.000 --> 02:44:30.000
what you did about the floaters and the screen height and the floaters' structures?

02:44:30.000 --> 02:44:31.000
Did you get into that?

02:44:31.000 --> 02:44:34.000
Tell you the truth.

02:44:34.000 --> 02:44:35.000
I was...

02:44:35.000 --> 02:44:39.000
I was at a lot of those meetings, but when it came down,

02:44:39.000 --> 02:44:48.000
I would only involve myself when it became time to say what we get ready to do.

02:44:48.000 --> 02:44:53.000
And when we're at the age we want you to go so and so and so.

02:44:53.000 --> 02:45:02.000
I didn't get into those philosophical conversations about Frantz Fanon,

02:45:02.000 --> 02:45:09.000
and Frantz Fanon of another thought or Frederick Douglass did.

02:45:09.000 --> 02:45:12.000
So I didn't get into all of that.

02:45:12.000 --> 02:45:17.000
If we were going to move on a situation, the strategy is this,

02:45:17.000 --> 02:45:20.000
if I look out at my moving in,

02:45:20.000 --> 02:45:24.000
and I go in to set up stuff, what would you want me to do?

02:45:24.000 --> 02:45:26.000
And then I go do it.

02:45:26.000 --> 02:45:27.000
That was my position.

02:45:27.000 --> 02:45:30.000
And I worked very well with Jim in doing that.

02:45:30.000 --> 02:45:35.000
I worked very well with McDoug and doing that.

02:45:35.000 --> 02:45:38.000
And that's kind of, I guess, why I...

02:45:38.000 --> 02:45:41.000
And Frederick Douglass, or the boss lady was,

02:45:41.000 --> 02:45:46.000
with perfect for getting me to do anything she needed me to do.

02:45:46.000 --> 02:45:48.000
What about the freedom rights?

02:45:48.000 --> 02:45:52.000
What was your thoughts on the freedom rights?

02:45:52.000 --> 02:45:58.000
Well, by the time the freedom rights had started, I was in McComb.

02:45:58.000 --> 02:46:07.000
And when they were coming back to Jackson returning in 61,

02:46:07.000 --> 02:46:12.000
we were making preparations for some of them to come down and work in McComb,

02:46:13.000 --> 02:46:14.000
in which we did.

02:46:14.000 --> 02:46:19.000
That's how Gwen Green and Travis Britt,

02:46:19.000 --> 02:46:25.000
and Ruby Doris Smith Robinson, her boyfriend, Billy, came down,

02:46:25.000 --> 02:46:34.000
and there was other freedom riders that came down to work on voter registration.

02:46:35.000 --> 02:46:42.000
I got only involved in the freedom rights in Alabama.

02:46:42.000 --> 02:46:50.000
One of my assignments was that once the...

02:46:50.000 --> 02:46:54.000
Once Montgomery said everybody could ride the buses,

02:46:54.000 --> 02:47:02.000
one of my jobs was to go into Montgomery and ride the bus up front.

02:47:05.000 --> 02:47:09.000
So, I'm here.

02:47:11.000 --> 02:47:14.000
And that's like after you know the...

02:47:14.000 --> 02:47:17.000
I contact people coming out the bus.

02:47:17.000 --> 02:47:23.000
Yeah, well, that's kind of where it was.

02:47:23.000 --> 02:47:29.000
And that's why I was a little skeptical

02:47:30.000 --> 02:47:32.000
when I got to...

02:47:32.000 --> 02:47:35.000
When I got when I was involved in this New York thing coming out of New York

02:47:35.000 --> 02:47:40.000
and Bill Hanson is announcing and going in the Cambridge,

02:47:40.000 --> 02:47:44.000
you had to go around into a dark corner where the bus stop is.

02:47:44.000 --> 02:47:49.000
And who knows who would have met us up in there?

02:47:49.000 --> 02:47:53.000
I mean, there was a certain amount of secrecy about this yet.

02:47:53.000 --> 02:47:55.000
I mean, did you did?

02:47:56.000 --> 02:48:08.000
You didn't just go frequently and now Bill is a professor in Nigeria or Lagos or somewhere.

02:48:08.000 --> 02:48:12.000
And I don't know how he felt, but at the 50th,

02:48:12.000 --> 02:48:16.000
he was the only one walking around in the Grand Bougain.

02:48:16.000 --> 02:48:19.000
I mean...

02:48:20.000 --> 02:48:25.000
So, I don't know.

02:48:26.000 --> 02:48:30.000
So, Hanson, I met Archim,

02:48:30.000 --> 02:48:33.000
I was providing you with two of my business channels.

02:48:33.000 --> 02:48:35.000
Yeah?

02:48:35.000 --> 02:48:36.000
Oh, it worked.

02:48:36.000 --> 02:48:39.000
It was a charm.

02:48:39.000 --> 02:48:40.000
He was...

02:48:40.000 --> 02:48:48.000
He too was somebody that you would listen to and you noted it had a knowledge of organization.

02:48:48.000 --> 02:48:50.000
And he was...

02:48:50.000 --> 02:48:53.000
He was somebody you could work with.

02:48:53.000 --> 02:48:58.000
And he was somebody you know you could walk, you could walk the line with.

02:48:58.000 --> 02:49:03.000
If you were in the struggle with him, you would air with him and he was with you.

02:49:03.000 --> 02:49:07.000
You weren't afraid to be out there.

02:49:07.000 --> 02:49:10.000
He was a good man.

02:49:18.000 --> 02:49:20.000
You ever in Albany?

02:49:20.000 --> 02:49:25.000
Yes, I was in Albany.

02:49:25.000 --> 02:49:39.000
One of the things about Albany is that the girls had gotten locked up.

02:49:39.000 --> 02:49:43.000
And Jim and I had went out to see about him.

02:49:44.000 --> 02:49:50.000
And we went on our way back and Jim had to go to the bathroom.

02:49:50.000 --> 02:49:54.000
So, Jim made this stop.

02:49:54.000 --> 02:50:02.000
And he went into this restaurant and went into this kind of film station.

02:50:02.000 --> 02:50:09.000
And he came back out in a hurry holding his self and he got back in the car.

02:50:09.000 --> 02:50:11.000
And I said, why are you holding this?

02:50:11.000 --> 02:50:13.000
I was in the go to the bathroom.

02:50:13.000 --> 02:50:15.000
He says, no.

02:50:15.000 --> 02:50:18.000
I said, he says, I'll hold it till I get down the road.

02:50:18.000 --> 02:50:20.000
That's what's wrong.

02:50:20.000 --> 02:50:23.000
He says, there was a guy in there with a gun.

02:50:23.000 --> 02:50:31.000
And I didn't think this was the proper opportunity to give up my life for the revolution just to take a piss.

02:50:31.000 --> 02:50:37.000
So, I decided to get back in the car and let it out down the road.

02:50:37.000 --> 02:50:43.000
So, that was just one little thing.

02:50:43.000 --> 02:50:52.000
But then, when I was one of my jobs at the height of what I was in there before a king came in.

02:50:52.000 --> 02:50:56.000
And I was helping Charles Sherrod to do some stuff.

02:50:56.000 --> 02:51:02.000
Then I was brought back in when all of King's men came in.

02:51:02.000 --> 02:51:11.000
And my job, because some of those guys knew me like YT and Andy and everybody.

02:51:11.000 --> 02:51:14.000
I could kind of slide around.

02:51:14.000 --> 02:51:19.000
So, my job was to hang around Dr. Anderson's house.

02:51:19.000 --> 02:51:25.000
They had a Dr. Anderson in Albany where they stayed.

02:51:25.000 --> 02:51:29.000
And just listen.

02:51:30.000 --> 02:51:33.000
I was just next by.

02:51:33.000 --> 02:51:35.000
Next day, it's the LC.

02:51:35.000 --> 02:51:45.000
But now, one night, I was sitting there and YT came to me and said, come on, take a ride with me.

02:51:45.000 --> 02:51:48.000
So, we got in the car.

02:51:48.000 --> 02:51:52.000
We drove to the jail.

02:51:52.000 --> 02:51:57.000
YTC, he had taken this train into dock.

02:51:57.000 --> 02:52:00.000
And they said, what?

02:52:00.000 --> 02:52:03.000
He said, take this train into dock.

02:52:03.000 --> 02:52:08.000
And they had made the deal with the chief of police.

02:52:08.000 --> 02:52:11.000
There was no food that would come in to dock.

02:52:11.000 --> 02:52:15.000
Not less, it came from the movement people.

02:52:15.000 --> 02:52:19.000
So, I said, I'm going to take this in.

02:52:19.000 --> 02:52:26.000
So, I said, I kind of say, oh, you're paying me back.

02:52:26.000 --> 02:52:36.000
And then, and him and Martin and Abernathy was in their cell.

02:52:36.000 --> 02:52:40.000
And they both had on a silk pajamas.

02:52:40.000 --> 02:52:43.000
And they were both laughing and talking.

02:52:43.000 --> 02:52:46.000
And I gave each one of them their trays.

02:52:46.000 --> 02:52:49.000
And Martin sat down and said, thank you.

02:52:49.000 --> 02:52:54.000
And immediately started eating old poke chops.

02:52:54.000 --> 02:52:57.000
I had nicknamed for Rev. Ralph Abernathy.

02:52:57.000 --> 02:53:04.000
Old poke chops looked at me and said, boy, they forgot to chuckle an ice cream.

02:53:04.000 --> 02:53:12.000
I said, yeah, but I ain't bringing it back to you.

02:53:12.000 --> 02:53:19.000
As I proceeded to say, Jella.

02:53:19.000 --> 02:53:23.000
So, I went back out of white, not late after.

02:53:23.000 --> 02:53:31.000
We went on back to the house and sat around and looked at some more and listened to some more and whatever.

02:53:31.000 --> 02:53:38.000
And then, you know, did what I had to do and follow Charles Sherrod orders.

02:53:38.000 --> 02:53:47.000
And went up in Baker, in Turral, and did voter registration and stuff like that.

02:53:47.000 --> 02:53:51.000
But I was only there for a very short period of time.

02:53:51.000 --> 02:53:53.000
In the early periods.

02:53:53.000 --> 02:53:58.000
And doing the big one is when I was really there.

02:53:58.000 --> 02:54:01.000
I spent time there.

02:54:01.000 --> 02:54:03.000
What about some?

02:54:03.000 --> 02:54:04.000
Did you go back to time?

02:54:04.000 --> 02:54:06.000
No, no, no.

02:54:06.000 --> 02:54:14.000
I never went back to Selma until, until, until, until, 19.

02:54:14.000 --> 02:54:17.000
When did Bob Moses take me down?

02:54:17.000 --> 02:54:20.000
Yeah.

02:54:20.000 --> 02:54:23.000
It was, it's just been maybe about eight and nine years ago.

02:54:23.000 --> 02:54:26.000
When they started to do believe stuff.

02:54:26.000 --> 02:54:30.000
He, he took me down in there.

02:54:30.000 --> 02:54:37.000
And I was really surprised to see all of the turkey wings and the festivities and everything.

02:54:37.000 --> 02:54:42.000
And he says, yeah, I just wanted to show you what's going on from your work.

02:54:42.000 --> 02:54:48.000
And then he took me to the folks that was involved in the Jubilee and everything.

02:54:48.000 --> 02:54:54.000
And he introduced me as the first snicker that landed in Selma.

02:54:54.000 --> 02:54:59.000
And of course, folks is, oh, you know, oh yeah, okay.

02:54:59.000 --> 02:55:02.000
And that was it.

02:55:02.000 --> 02:55:05.000
But that was about it.

02:55:05.000 --> 02:55:07.000
So then...

02:55:07.000 --> 02:55:08.000
Right.

02:55:08.000 --> 02:55:16.000
And so then I would go down every year because Bob Moses would do his thing.

02:55:16.000 --> 02:55:18.000
And the Jubilee would do his thing.

02:55:18.000 --> 02:55:22.000
Bob Moses had an organization called the Trail.

02:55:22.000 --> 02:55:30.000
And the Trail was made up of people that was up at the, at the center of things in Lowndes County.

02:55:30.000 --> 02:55:35.000
That's where the Tent City was on 80.

02:55:35.000 --> 02:55:38.000
Right there where they put that incentive center there.

02:55:38.000 --> 02:55:42.000
And they're still trying to get Bob Moses's information.

02:55:42.000 --> 02:55:47.000
And Bob Moses's family's still ain't going to put it in there because he didn't want them to have it.

02:55:47.000 --> 02:55:49.000
Was that Tent City?

02:55:49.000 --> 02:55:51.000
Was that from the building?

02:55:51.000 --> 02:55:52.000
The basement lounge?

02:55:52.000 --> 02:55:54.000
That was from the march.

02:55:54.000 --> 02:55:58.000
And you didn't have a go in the lounge?

02:55:58.000 --> 02:56:02.000
Did you ever go to the park lounge or the dining room?

02:56:02.000 --> 02:56:03.000
No, no, no, no.

02:56:03.000 --> 02:56:10.000
I hooked up with Bob Moses later on and about doing some other kinds of stuff.

02:56:10.000 --> 02:56:13.000
But we were always in touch.

02:56:13.000 --> 02:56:15.000
You can have them all the time, right?

02:56:15.000 --> 02:56:16.000
Yeah.

02:56:16.000 --> 02:56:19.000
More house and all of that.

02:56:19.000 --> 02:56:22.000
And that brother's got him and Joanne.

02:56:22.000 --> 02:56:25.000
Man's came out of...

02:56:25.000 --> 02:56:27.000
In Albany?

02:56:27.000 --> 02:56:29.000
Because Joanne is from Albany.

02:56:29.000 --> 02:56:32.000
Yeah, that's how he met.

02:56:32.000 --> 02:56:35.000
Right, right, right.

02:56:35.000 --> 02:56:37.000
You remember that picture, right?

02:56:37.000 --> 02:56:42.000
I love being...

02:56:42.000 --> 02:56:50.000
She became a friend, she became a close mother kind of thing.

02:56:50.000 --> 02:56:58.000
I guess I got close to her because of the relationship of my mother and her.

02:56:58.000 --> 02:57:12.000
And when I was changing over from the tidings campaign going back in the field for the

02:57:12.000 --> 02:57:19.000
Doudalabian for the MFTP, Miss Hamer was in DC

02:57:19.000 --> 02:57:27.000
So I got Miss Hamer, Miss Baker, they come over and my mom was fixed lunch for them

02:57:27.000 --> 02:57:36.000
and my mom's in Miss Baker had a real old girl get together kind of thing.

02:57:36.000 --> 02:57:53.000
When I got married the night before I got married Ella and Joanne Grant took me out and got me drunk.

02:57:54.000 --> 02:58:01.000
Trying to make sure that I am doing what I intend to do.

02:58:01.000 --> 02:58:06.000
And then I of course got married at Harry Belafonte's house.

02:58:06.000 --> 02:58:13.000
And of course my mother was there and of course Ella and my mother.

02:58:13.000 --> 02:58:22.000
Of course knowing each other was like my support pieces.

02:58:22.000 --> 02:58:27.000
Ella was Mama.

02:58:27.000 --> 02:58:29.000
When I ran into...

02:58:29.000 --> 02:58:33.000
Like when I was in...

02:58:33.000 --> 02:58:40.000
Before I left Cambridge in between things things got kind of tough.

02:58:40.000 --> 02:58:54.000
And I was having trouble at home with my mom's and I was actually...

02:58:54.000 --> 02:59:00.000
I was actually having trouble in Cambridge and I needed some time out.

02:59:00.000 --> 02:59:14.000
So Ella suggested that I go talk to Joe Baker who was on the Medical Committee for Human Rights and she was a psychiatrist.

02:59:14.000 --> 02:59:18.000
So Miss Baker suggested that I go talk to her.

02:59:18.000 --> 02:59:25.000
And when I went to talk to Joe of course she says, you ain't crazy.

02:59:25.000 --> 02:59:31.000
You just mixed up a lot of stuff that you can't figure out right now.

02:59:31.000 --> 02:59:42.000
So what we're going to do is we're going to send you to not mount Eagle.

02:59:42.000 --> 02:59:49.000
Peekskill. Peekskill in New York for about a week.

02:59:49.000 --> 02:59:56.000
And what you're going to do up there is just rest, read, do everything you know.

02:59:56.000 --> 03:00:00.000
And then at the end of the week there's a fundraiser.

03:00:00.000 --> 03:00:09.000
The Paul Robeson fundraiser when Paul Robeson is the history of when Paul Robeson spoke in Peekskill.

03:00:09.000 --> 03:00:14.000
And John Hammond Jr. is going to be on the program and everything.

03:00:14.000 --> 03:00:17.000
And you're going to just take yourself a little rest.

03:00:17.000 --> 03:00:20.000
So I went to Peekskill.

03:00:20.000 --> 03:00:23.000
Had lots of fun.

03:00:23.000 --> 03:00:29.000
And spoke on what I knew about Paul, but Paul Robeson.

03:00:29.000 --> 03:00:36.000
And then got a surprise of being taken to Sam and Helen Roverson's house.

03:00:36.000 --> 03:00:46.000
Who Sam, Sam Roverson was the doctor that went to Russia to bring back Paul Robeson.

03:00:46.000 --> 03:00:55.000
And while I'm sitting there in Katonah, New York outside resting my feces in the good sun,

03:00:55.000 --> 03:01:00.000
this big black man comes out and sits next to me with this deep voice.

03:01:00.000 --> 03:01:05.000
And we introduce ourselves in damn for any Paul Robeson.

03:01:06.000 --> 03:01:14.000
So then Doc comes out and they had such a house that they had a sauna.

03:01:14.000 --> 03:01:21.000
And you walk to the sauna and then you walk down these stairs and you get under this natural stream.

03:01:21.000 --> 03:01:28.000
So there's here's us men in this sauna, buck naked, running out, running down under this Jesus,

03:01:28.000 --> 03:01:37.000
ice cold mountain water and just talking and I am with Paul Robeson.

03:01:37.000 --> 03:01:44.000
Well, I can't thank Ella enough for taking me out of this situation.

03:01:44.000 --> 03:01:52.000
So I go back into Cambridge and I'm revitalized now and I've gotten all my stuff together as to what I'm doing.

03:01:53.000 --> 03:01:58.000
So I'm talking to Ruby about what's going on and what I'm feeling and what's happening.

03:01:58.000 --> 03:02:08.000
So Ruby's saying, well that's when we began the process of my moving out because one of the other things that Gloria did was

03:02:08.000 --> 03:02:15.000
Gloria tried to petition Atlanta for me to stay and it was really time for me to go.

03:02:15.000 --> 03:02:19.000
And so that became a bone of contention.

03:02:20.000 --> 03:02:23.000
Did you feel like they could do it in your own house?

03:02:23.000 --> 03:02:25.000
Yeah.

03:02:25.000 --> 03:02:29.000
But I knew that they were on and on.

03:02:29.000 --> 03:02:35.000
Well, I got rid of all of the surrounding people like like,

03:02:37.000 --> 03:02:46.000
as I said, the NAACP and all of the big organizations was coming in once we got things going when the students were coming in.

03:02:46.000 --> 03:02:51.000
So now the board is taking care of and taking care of the situation.

03:02:51.000 --> 03:02:57.000
But there was this other group coming in.

03:02:57.000 --> 03:03:07.000
With Carol Rogoff, this reporter was very hot on Carol

03:03:07.000 --> 03:03:14.000
So I got Carol to get this reporter to take me for a ride.

03:03:14.000 --> 03:03:23.000
And we had a little conversation about silk suits and denim and guys who were denim.

03:03:23.000 --> 03:03:28.000
And they organized us who worked in denim closer to the people, local people.

03:03:28.000 --> 03:03:34.000
And the ones that's in these shiny silk suits are coming in making collections.

03:03:34.000 --> 03:03:37.000
Well, the story got out the next day.

03:03:37.000 --> 03:03:42.000
And of course, the local folks wanted to know where such a story came from.

03:03:42.000 --> 03:03:51.000
But they all linked it back to the NAACP and they chased them out of town.

03:03:51.000 --> 03:03:57.000
So the local board then began the run-in business.

03:03:57.000 --> 03:04:06.000
And they had nobody else outside of SNCC who was not making any turf kind of...

03:04:06.000 --> 03:04:10.000
Right, right, right, right.

03:04:10.000 --> 03:04:12.000
You were building the organization.

03:04:12.000 --> 03:04:18.000
But we were making good on what SNCC was doing in Cambridge.

03:04:18.000 --> 03:04:22.000
And Cambridge was doing okay.

03:04:22.000 --> 03:04:29.000
So it wasn't necessary for us to control as the big organization.

03:04:29.000 --> 03:04:39.000
The idea was you make these things and then you control them and then you last for hundreds and hundreds of years.

03:04:39.000 --> 03:04:42.000
That's the end of the day?

03:04:42.000 --> 03:04:45.000
Well, yeah.

03:04:45.000 --> 03:04:51.000
And the NAACP has come a long way and done a damn good fight and still doing a good fight.

03:04:51.000 --> 03:04:54.000
But their fight isn't the only fight.

03:04:54.000 --> 03:04:58.000
They take the fight to the point of the courts.

03:04:58.000 --> 03:05:05.000
But there's always the courts are part of the system which has a certain amount of dictation.

03:05:05.000 --> 03:05:11.000
But just like what's happening today, you got to push the envelope.

03:05:11.000 --> 03:05:14.000
I grew up in Baltimore.

03:05:14.000 --> 03:05:20.000
All of that stuff that happened last week from Freddie Gray just didn't happen.

03:05:21.000 --> 03:05:23.000
People have been out of work.

03:05:23.000 --> 03:05:29.000
People have been taken away from opportunities.

03:05:29.000 --> 03:05:32.000
I got a cousin that lives in Pikesville MD.

03:05:32.000 --> 03:05:38.000
You have to, when you go in out to her house, you have to come up righteous to up Pikesville MD.

03:05:38.000 --> 03:05:47.000
And if you get to Pikesville MD and Pikesville MD, or one side to street is the Pikesville MD.

03:05:48.000 --> 03:05:54.000
Multimillion dollar operation on this side of the street is junkies.

03:05:54.000 --> 03:05:56.000
Land in the street.

03:05:56.000 --> 03:05:59.000
It does not make any sense.

03:05:59.000 --> 03:06:04.000
This side of the street is the Jewish community clean.

03:06:04.000 --> 03:06:07.000
This side of the street is junkies.

03:06:07.000 --> 03:06:10.000
Multimillion dollar operation sitting here.

03:06:10.000 --> 03:06:12.000
Downtown Baltimore.

03:06:12.000 --> 03:06:13.000
You got to walk.

03:06:13.000 --> 03:06:16.000
You got all of that money coming in and people coming in.

03:06:16.000 --> 03:06:23.000
And by you got the Pikesville MD gambling and going on and you come three four blocks.

03:06:23.000 --> 03:06:25.000
Nothing.

03:06:25.000 --> 03:06:28.000
You got people out of work.

03:06:28.000 --> 03:06:35.000
You got black people that will walk down to the to the to the wall, going to Philips and will look different.

03:06:35.000 --> 03:06:38.000
Look at you differently.

03:06:38.000 --> 03:06:48.000
And ain't nothing changed in Baltimore until something comes about in all of these cities.

03:06:48.000 --> 03:06:56.000
If they chase that dude out of Chicago, what's going to take his place?

03:06:56.000 --> 03:07:01.000
Yeah, yeah, yeah, what's going to take his place?

03:07:01.000 --> 03:07:06.000
It looked like they may or may not have fixed this guy in Baltimore.

03:07:06.000 --> 03:07:08.000
But the police are part of the problem.

03:07:08.000 --> 03:07:15.000
The police are probably the police are part of the power.

03:07:15.000 --> 03:07:17.000
And the power is which controls.

03:07:17.000 --> 03:07:21.000
That's what's controlling all of these wars and everything else.

03:07:21.000 --> 03:07:28.000
They said on this television this morning that they're going to take away people's oil

03:07:28.000 --> 03:07:32.000
in order to stop them from killing people.

03:07:32.000 --> 03:07:36.000
Well, you take away somebody else's income.

03:07:36.000 --> 03:07:39.000
What are they supposed to do? What fight you?

03:07:39.000 --> 03:07:42.000
So you just same thing in Baltimore.

03:07:42.000 --> 03:07:46.000
The same thing in Chicago, the same thing in Ferguson.

03:07:46.000 --> 03:07:48.000
They got to do it.

03:07:48.000 --> 03:07:51.000
And we, we can play a role.

03:07:51.000 --> 03:07:55.000
And it seems to me to be very simple.

03:07:56.000 --> 03:08:03.000
There's more rich black folks today than there was in 1920.

03:08:03.000 --> 03:08:10.000
There seems to me that there ought to be enough, they have guts enough

03:08:10.000 --> 03:08:16.000
to put the money together and come to the poker table and play the game.

03:08:16.000 --> 03:08:20.000
We can do laundry bats.

03:08:21.000 --> 03:08:26.000
We can do computer and we can get together with one of them companies

03:08:26.000 --> 03:08:29.000
that do the computer tools.

03:08:29.000 --> 03:08:34.000
We can teach people to get jobs, decent jobs to make a living.

03:08:34.000 --> 03:08:37.000
And that's where I think we ought to go.

03:08:37.000 --> 03:08:39.000
I think that's the direction.

03:08:39.000 --> 03:08:45.000
I think that's the direction because voter registration is leading us to people

03:08:46.000 --> 03:08:53.000
who elected on the hill that I don't see any difference in them having.

03:08:53.000 --> 03:08:59.000
I don't know exactly how Congress works, but they work from rules.

03:08:59.000 --> 03:09:04.000
So when you become a part of the rule, then you become a part of the problem.

03:09:04.000 --> 03:09:08.000
So you can't do this because this rule goes over here.

03:09:08.000 --> 03:09:12.000
You can't do this because this rule's over here.

03:09:13.000 --> 03:09:16.000
Just because I'm no different than anybody else.

03:09:16.000 --> 03:09:20.000
When they say you're going to have a black president, I consider I start thinking

03:09:20.000 --> 03:09:24.000
that my world is going to become different.

03:09:24.000 --> 03:09:27.000
My world is going to become different.

03:09:27.000 --> 03:09:33.000
I did not expect no black president, the whole no no no no no no no.

03:09:33.000 --> 03:09:39.000
Be a conference after another black man has been stopped in his doorway

03:09:40.000 --> 03:09:46.000
and locked up for going in his own house and he's got to sit down and pick up an appeasement.

03:09:46.000 --> 03:09:49.000
No no no no no.

03:09:49.000 --> 03:09:52.000
There's something wrong.

03:09:52.000 --> 03:09:53.000
That's not from position.

03:09:53.000 --> 03:09:54.000
That's not from position.

03:09:54.000 --> 03:09:57.000
We're not in power.

03:09:57.000 --> 03:10:02.000
And these boys that sit up on the hill, God bless them.

03:10:02.000 --> 03:10:06.000
But they ain't doing no different than the boys did in construction.

03:10:06.000 --> 03:10:11.000
Except too many of them may have spitting tobacco on the side.

03:10:11.000 --> 03:10:20.000
But I don't know about, I know that voter registration leads to new leadership.

03:10:20.000 --> 03:10:27.000
And new leadership leads to change in a sense.

03:10:27.000 --> 03:10:35.000
Ferguson now has a chance of changing because now more black people are involved in the process.

03:10:36.000 --> 03:10:41.000
What do you think of Smith's move towards black power?

03:10:41.000 --> 03:10:44.000
What do you think of Smith's move towards black power?

03:10:44.000 --> 03:10:47.000
As exactly what I'm talking about now.

03:10:47.000 --> 03:10:53.000
The move towards black power was not to use guns.

03:10:53.000 --> 03:10:56.000
Was not to use guns.

03:10:57.000 --> 03:11:12.000
They threw the media through the whole thing off when they could latch on to Bobby Seale and the rest of them with a gun plane.

03:11:12.000 --> 03:11:17.000
I mean we were talking about the same thing that I'm talking about now.

03:11:17.000 --> 03:11:25.000
Opportunities to make money in order to create money for people to make money to buy houses.

03:11:26.000 --> 03:11:45.000
To be able to control schools, to be able to get recreation centers, to do things for kids, to make kids grow, and do things in our community that we know that we want to have our own religions and do what we want to do without being dominated by it.

03:11:45.000 --> 03:11:49.000
We were not talking about guns.

03:11:49.000 --> 03:11:54.000
Because we know we can't win with guns. The Indians didn't win with guns.

03:11:54.000 --> 03:11:59.000
And nobody else had won with guns in this.

03:11:59.000 --> 03:12:08.000
When I think when Japan was trying to make some kind of deal that dropped a bomb on them over there and locked up everybody over here.

03:12:08.000 --> 03:12:12.000
You can't deal with these people that way.

03:12:12.000 --> 03:12:33.000
So if we had our own, if we had our base functioning in such a sense that they knew that we would come after them, the black politicians as well as the white ones, with a power base coming from a power base.

03:12:33.000 --> 03:12:50.000
Some of these entrepreneurs that have made money. Some of these black folks that live in the water gate. Some of these ones that don't have to worry about it coming back on them that they can do things without it coming back on.

03:12:50.000 --> 03:12:53.000
Put that money together.

03:12:53.000 --> 03:12:58.000
And let's go out and fight.

03:13:02.000 --> 03:13:08.000
Did you have an ordinary to go back in Mississippi after you left my home?

03:13:08.000 --> 03:13:13.000
Yeah, I was with the child of the vote in Mississippi.

03:13:13.000 --> 03:13:22.000
So do you have anything else to think about?

03:13:22.000 --> 03:13:25.000
Yeah.

03:13:25.000 --> 03:13:28.000
I can't help me out there.

03:13:28.000 --> 03:13:32.000
I can't ask you anything else.

03:13:32.000 --> 03:13:35.000
All right.

03:13:35.000 --> 03:13:38.000
I can't unhide you with this.

03:13:38.000 --> 03:13:43.000
What do you want people to know about the movement?

03:13:43.000 --> 03:14:04.000
That we were lucky enough to have somebody like Ella Baker to present us with a very, very simple plan as taking people from where they are and bringing them up.

03:14:05.000 --> 03:14:17.000
Those that are already on top don't necessarily need to push, but they need to support those from the bottom.

03:14:17.000 --> 03:14:33.000
And those from the bottom would understand what the opportunities are for them and given the opportunity to look at that and examine that, then more people would move on their own and make decisions.

03:14:34.000 --> 03:14:45.000
Based on their need, which would be, I think, I think that the majority of folks would begin to see that we all need the same thing.

03:14:45.000 --> 03:14:51.000
And it would be easier to come together.

03:14:51.000 --> 03:15:01.000
So I think that we left folks with us.

03:15:01.000 --> 03:15:06.000
Something that I think that wasn't dealt with in any other movement.

03:15:06.000 --> 03:15:13.000
We dealt with the thing that let folks know that they are the leaders.

03:15:13.000 --> 03:15:17.000
But there's no one leader.

03:15:17.000 --> 03:15:22.000
If you get up and you want to do something, somebody's going to follow you.

03:15:22.000 --> 03:15:25.000
But you got to go and do what you want.

03:15:25.000 --> 03:15:28.000
You got to know that you want to do something.

03:15:28.000 --> 03:15:31.000
And you become a leader then.

03:15:31.000 --> 03:15:37.000
And if enough people do that, then we have a movement.

03:15:37.000 --> 03:15:42.000
We don't need another Martin Luther King.

03:15:42.000 --> 03:15:55.000
And that was one of the things that we tried and still trying to get away from.

03:15:55.000 --> 03:16:01.000
Even that movie that Oprah did.

03:16:01.000 --> 03:16:18.000
I mean, she used a lot of money to tell a story that could have been told a totally different way and give up a lot of information that it would have been true instead of some factual, unfactual situation.

03:16:18.000 --> 03:16:30.000
And compared that to the one that Robinson did called Freedom Song, where he depicted us going into Mississippi,

03:16:30.000 --> 03:16:46.000
registering people to vote, getting the people involved as opposed to having Jim and John sitting in front of a conference with Jose reprimanding Jim Forman.

03:16:46.000 --> 03:16:50.000
That has never happened.

03:16:50.000 --> 03:16:53.000
Jim was not that kind of person.

03:16:53.000 --> 03:16:55.000
Jim was as old as Martin.

03:16:55.000 --> 03:17:02.000
Jim was as more of a leader than Martin.

03:17:02.000 --> 03:17:18.000
And Jim had his own organization and was aware of the fact of having his own organization and having the strength of backing of his own people to say any damn thing he needed to say.

03:17:18.000 --> 03:17:27.000
And at that point, we were already been chased out of Selma.

03:17:27.000 --> 03:17:39.000
And he's already chased out of, I'm not Selma, but chased out of Southwest Georgia with them blastering in and not leaving anything.

03:17:39.000 --> 03:17:40.000
Right.

03:17:40.000 --> 03:17:45.000
Now what I'm talking about the movie, I'm talking about Oprah, right.

03:17:45.000 --> 03:17:58.000
And then Oprah in a car, and then John in a car with Martin driving and Martin talking, that's bullshit.

03:17:58.000 --> 03:18:03.000
Martin ain't drove no damn way.

03:18:03.000 --> 03:18:08.000
And we didn't put John Lewis out.

03:18:08.000 --> 03:18:12.000
It was John Lewis's choice to leave.

03:18:12.000 --> 03:18:22.000
Always believed that he wanted to be an SCLC person anyway because he was brought up under that preacher, Jim Lawson,

03:18:22.000 --> 03:18:31.000
loved that neighbor, Gandhi, whatever that stuff was.

03:18:31.000 --> 03:18:34.000
I mean,

03:18:34.000 --> 03:18:37.000
Were you at the meeting where I felt he was elected?

03:18:37.000 --> 03:18:39.000
No, no, I wouldn't need either.

03:18:39.000 --> 03:18:42.000
I wouldn't need either.

03:18:42.000 --> 03:18:58.000
But Oprah could have used her money to do a different, if she wanted to do anything she should have shown the relationship that went on.

03:18:58.000 --> 03:19:01.000
Because they were scared to death in Selma.

03:19:01.000 --> 03:19:05.000
And they were scared to death in Albany, Georgia.

03:19:05.000 --> 03:19:11.000
And each place they were telling us, don't do this. You all won't get killed.

03:19:11.000 --> 03:19:20.000
The same thing that adult advisors was telling us everywhere, just stop.

03:19:20.000 --> 03:19:23.000
So...

03:19:23.000 --> 03:19:26.000
Yeah, it's not a very good depiction of the movie.

03:19:26.000 --> 03:19:30.000
No, no, no.

03:19:31.000 --> 03:19:33.000
Right. And they...

03:19:33.000 --> 03:19:36.000
For some reason they want to...

03:19:37.000 --> 03:19:41.000
They want to either rewrite the history or write us out.

03:19:41.000 --> 03:19:48.000
And that's one of the things I think the value of the SNCC Legacy Project is.

03:19:48.000 --> 03:19:58.000
Because it's coming back in a way that allows us to say and do what we know to do, which is organized.

03:19:58.000 --> 03:20:05.000
I just got to email asking what to do, when to do, raising money and everything.

03:20:05.000 --> 03:20:07.000
And I responded, I'm available.

03:20:07.000 --> 03:20:09.000
Except for a couple of things.

03:20:09.000 --> 03:20:13.000
I got to take piano lessons and recognize them dates.

03:20:13.000 --> 03:20:15.000
And I'm trying to get some new needs.

03:20:15.000 --> 03:20:17.000
So those are the only things.

03:20:17.000 --> 03:20:19.000
Otherwise, I'm available to move.

03:20:19.000 --> 03:20:26.000
If you want me to go down into Selma and go down into Ferguson to talk to some of them, I'll go.

03:20:27.000 --> 03:20:35.000
And whatever you need me to do, if you don't conflict with my obligations, I'm free to go.

03:20:35.000 --> 03:20:38.000
I still play the same role, if you need me.

03:20:38.000 --> 03:20:42.000
If you need me, if you don't need me, leave me alone and I go fishing.

03:20:42.000 --> 03:20:46.000
Which is something I love to do.

03:20:46.000 --> 03:20:49.000
Any final thoughts?

03:20:49.000 --> 03:20:52.000
Any minute?

03:20:56.000 --> 03:21:25.000
I guess it's my dream to see a group of black folks come together in a financial kind of situation that's honest enough and got enough guts to not to be worried about consequences, but to be worried about a program and what's moving ahead and use our resources for what we know we can use them for.

03:21:25.000 --> 03:21:32.000
And it's simple kinds of things that we can get involved in and help our community to grow.

03:21:32.000 --> 03:21:46.000
Such as if we had a bank on the corner that could loan, that could loan, Miss Johnson, $25 to open up a laundromat,

03:21:46.000 --> 03:21:55.000
loan, build Henry, $25 to open up a pool hall and that money comes back as some recreation.

03:21:55.000 --> 03:21:59.000
Somebody else may want a restaurant.

03:21:59.000 --> 03:22:08.000
Maybe we can talk one of these companies, one of these high tech companies are coming into a small town like Greenwood.

03:22:08.000 --> 03:22:17.000
And Red Brown had a manufacturing company going on called Mace.

03:22:17.000 --> 03:22:20.000
Where they made denim.

03:22:20.000 --> 03:22:30.000
Why can't we find outlets and then let that money roll around in the community before it goes on.

03:22:30.000 --> 03:22:34.000
Then it can go out on the stock exchange.

03:22:34.000 --> 03:22:47.000
Henry G. Parks Jr, who I mentioned earlier on, they didn't find out that he owned Parks Sausage Co.

03:22:47.000 --> 03:22:53.000
You know what Parks Sausage Co is? Parks Sausage Co is a sausage that's been out for years.

03:22:53.000 --> 03:22:58.000
And it had a commercial called Bob Moses Mopalk sausage.

03:22:58.000 --> 03:23:01.000
But it was a black, it was known as a black home business.

03:23:01.000 --> 03:23:04.000
But everybody thought it was owned by Henry G. Parks Jr.

03:23:04.000 --> 03:23:08.000
But it was actually owned by Henry G. Parks Jr.

03:23:08.000 --> 03:23:14.000
And until it went on the stock exchange, nobody knew that it was owned by Henry G. Parks Jr.

03:23:14.000 --> 03:23:26.000
But Henry G. Parks Jr was pushing money around in the community from a policy book.

03:23:26.000 --> 03:23:41.000
Now if one man can have all of this business, he had businesses from Pikesville MD from Pikesville MD down to Pikesville MD.

03:23:42.000 --> 03:23:49.000
He owned a Royal Theatre, which was all a part of the Chitlin' Circuit.

03:23:49.000 --> 03:24:01.000
I'm saying if one man can take his finances, he sent his wife to the Victorine Q. Adams.

03:24:01.000 --> 03:24:07.000
If one black man can put this kind of money together and do these kinds of things,

03:24:07.000 --> 03:24:17.000
just think of maybe seven or eight putting in some money and going to work.

03:24:17.000 --> 03:24:25.000
And when the clan walk up and say, you can't do this, fuck you.

03:24:26.000 --> 03:24:28.000
We got enough to do it.

03:24:28.000 --> 03:24:29.000
And I understand.

03:24:29.000 --> 03:24:34.000
And somebody told me, says, well, Reg, once you build this kind of thing,

03:24:34.000 --> 03:24:37.000
the bigger people will come in and buy it.

03:24:37.000 --> 03:24:40.000
I said, well, then that makes it even better.

03:24:40.000 --> 03:24:44.000
Because if we got something small here and the bigger people want to buy,

03:24:44.000 --> 03:24:48.000
that means that more economics is coming down in here.

03:24:48.000 --> 03:24:50.000
And that's where we want to see.

03:24:50.000 --> 03:24:52.000
It want to see it grow.

03:24:52.000 --> 03:24:55.000
So we don't want to see it to stop.

03:24:55.000 --> 03:25:02.000
So if that can happen, I love to see that happen.

03:25:02.000 --> 03:25:07.000
Somebody could say, you can talk to somebody.

03:25:07.000 --> 03:25:10.000
You can say it works there.

03:25:10.000 --> 03:25:15.000
That's it every day.

03:25:15.000 --> 03:25:24.000
Well, I can't thank you enough for bringing to the Congress to have the chance to do these things.

03:25:24.000 --> 03:25:30.000
Well, it all has something to do with me too.

03:25:30.000 --> 03:25:36.000
USA Today just did a thing with me and I suppose we'll be coming out soon.

03:25:36.000 --> 03:25:39.000
I was looking for that report and didn't find it.

03:25:39.000 --> 03:25:44.000
And there's other kinds of questions that's coming up about me.

03:25:44.000 --> 03:25:47.000
So and then,

03:25:47.000 --> 03:25:51.000
legacy is trying to pull stuff together for us to do things.

03:25:51.000 --> 03:25:55.000
So I figured it.

03:25:55.000 --> 03:25:57.000
Right.

03:25:57.000 --> 03:25:59.000
And for whatever reasons,

03:25:59.000 --> 03:26:04.000
you know my policy of somebody coming up and asking me for an interview.

03:26:04.000 --> 03:26:09.000
But if it's done in the context of what the legacy is doing,

03:26:09.000 --> 03:26:13.000
then and you go to Charlie and Charlie proves it and everything.

03:26:13.000 --> 03:26:19.000
That's cool with me, but still if anybody comes to me,

03:26:19.000 --> 03:26:21.000
you know the policy.

03:26:21.000 --> 03:26:24.000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress

03:26:24.000 --> 03:26:30.000
and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.
